"Faust" was also turned into a play by this guy, H P Grattan, in 1842, just a year before Poe used "Thulé" in "The Pit and the Pendulum."

Poe uses "Thulé" twice in his writing. He uses "ultma Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum," but in "Dream-Land," he uses "Thulé" at the beginning and end of the poem, like bookends. You can almost think of "The King of Thulé" and "Dream-Land" as going together. In "Dream-Land," the speaker talks about this dark, lonely place called Thulé, where he's haunted by dead friends and everything is gray and lifeless.  You can see the same feelings in "The King of Thulé," where Goethe's king is also lonely, lost, and doesn't want to live anymore. It's like Poe stepped right into Goethe's poem.

Goethe was a big deal, and Poe would have known about him, especially since Poe loved Tennyson. When someone asked Poe if he admired Tennyson, he said, "Yes, and Goethe!" Aside from that connection to Tennyson, Poe would have read a lot of Goethe's stuff because it was being reprinted a lot after it first came out.

So, this lady, Jennifer Palmer, took a spill in a grocery store 'cause some applesauce was left sittin' on the floor.  Now, she's sayin' the store manager, this Martin fella, knew about the spill,  heard about it twice, but didn't do nothin' about it for half an hour 'cause he was eatin' dinner.  She wants to sue him for damages, not just for her hurt, but 'cause she says he acted real mean and reckless.

Now, the judge ain't gonna toss her case out right away. To get those extra damages, she's gotta prove Martin knew he was doin' somethin' dangerous, that he was basically messin' with folks' safety on purpose. She's gonna say, see, other folks had slipped and fallen there before, so Martin shoulda known better.  

Whether he acted real bad, that's a bit harder to say. The judge might think it was just plain dumb, not necessarily mean, but it ain't lookin' good for Martin. 

Here's the deal: 

This Rich Wayne, he works at the store, tells Martin about the applesauce spill around 5:00. Martin says he's on a break and doesn't wanna deal with it. Then, Mary Haddigan, another worker, tells Martin about the spill again at 5:15, same story from Martin.

Finally, at 5:30, Palmer comes along, slips on that applesauce, and bam! Bad back.

It turns out, this ain't the first time folks have fallen in this store. Five times already that year, folks had gone down.  Palmer's sayin' Martin knew or shoulda known things were dangerous and didn't do nothin'.

Well, lemme tell ya somethin'.  A few years back, I took this class on Islam, and we got into a real hollerin' match about whether it was a religion that wanted to bash yer head in or not.  Now, more than ever, that question's got me scratchin' my head.  Look at how things've changed since 9/11.  The media, they went from slammin' Islam and them extremists to coddlin' it like a baby.  I'll bet you a dang dollar we couldn't have had a fella like Barack Obama runnin' for president back then, what with his Muslim roots and all. 

Now, I gotta say, this story 'bout Muhammad, the prophet fella, it got me thinkin'.  See, I figured Muhammad was a real tough hombre, the kinda guy who'd take over tribes and force 'em to turn Muslim.  But this here biography, it paints him as some kind of martyr, misunderstood and humble.  Like folks just kinda wandered in, saw the light, and joined up.  Seems fishy to me, like they're tryin' to make him out to be somethin' he ain't.

And get this, there's some real spooky similarities between Muhammad and Jesus.  Like when he turned some mutton and milk into enough for forty guys.  It's like they're tryin' to steal Jesus' thunder, makin' Muhammad look all holy and miraculous too.  Ain't that a kick in the pants?

Then there's all these stories about folks convertin' on their own, but they're all secondhand accounts, hear-say, somethin' like "So-and-so told me that So-and-so said..."  Gives me the creeps, makes it all sound like a bunch of baloney.

But the thing that really gets my goat is how they try to make Muhammad out to be this sweet talkin', wise guy.  But history says somethin' different, and I just can't help but wonder if Muslims today know the real deal about how Muhammad came to power.

Well, let me tell you somethin'.  After Jesus kicked the bucket, folks started preachin' about him in ways he probably wouldn't have liked.  Seems like Christianity got further and further from its roots over the years.  Nowadays, folks are gettin' more open-minded and wantin' things to change.  Some old-timers, though, they cling to the old ways and don't want nothin' new.  But they ain't gonna be the ones callin' the shots.  In time, more and more Christians are gonna want to go back to the basics, the stuff Jesus actually taught.  It might take a while, maybe even a hundred years or more, but it's gonna happen.  

Think of it like rewindin' a tape.  We're gonna strip away all the extra stuff that got added over the years and get back to what Jesus was all about.  It's gonna start slow, but then it'll pick up steam.  Folks are gonna start thinkin' more like they did back when Jesus was around.  And guess what?  The churches, they'll be right there leadin' the way!  But instead of everyone bein' different, we'll all start thinkin' alike.  Like when different teams all join together to win a game.  

History's full of these big turnarounds.  Remember when Christians were bein' persecuted by the Romans?  Well, look what happened!  The Romans became Christians themselves!  And in our own country, we went from slaves to leaders.   

This time, it's gonna be the same thing, only with religion.  We're gonna go back to the start, back to Jesus, and everybody's gonna be on the same page.   One thing that'll help this happen is folks startin' to see Jesus' words as somethin' more like a story, not just plain facts.   

So, what happened after Jesus?  Well, if you go way back, you see that it all started with Judaism.   They believed in one God, and they had these special books called the scriptures that they thought came from God.   The Jewish people weren't all on the same page, though.  There were different groups, like the Sadducees, the Pharisees, and the Essenes.  But they all shared some basic beliefs.

You see, this book, "The Jungle," it shows us that folks deep down, they're just out for themselves. They wanna make their lives as good as they can be, but they don't give a hoot about anyone less fortunate. It's all about lookin' out number one. Take those factory bosses, for example. They just wanna make their factories bigger and richer,  not a darn bit of care about who gets hurt in the process.  The book says it plain as day, these factories are like monsters, belchin' out smoke like it's nobody's business. They don't care about the people or the animals, just their bottom line. They're like those guys who drive their big trucks and don't even look when they pull out, runnin' over anything in their way. 

And those factory bosses, they don't care about their workers neither. They're just lookin' to squeeze every last penny they can out of 'em. They work 'em 'til they drop, then fire 'em without a second thought.  The whole place is just a mess of jealousy and hatred, everyone's lookin' out for themselves, 'cause nobody's lookin' out for 'em. These workers, they're like slaves, trapped in this system where they ain't got no rights. Unions are supposed to help, but they're just another bunch of guys lookin' to make a buck off the backs of the poor. You got folks workin' themselves to death, and nobody even cares. It's a real shame, a real travesty.

So, this book writer, Fitzgerald, he's got tricks up his sleeve to make you feel a certain way about stuff.  He's like a magician with words, ya know? Sometimes he'll pair words together that don't usually go together, just to give ya a vibe. Other times, he picks a thing, like a color, and makes it mean somethin' special, then he uses that special meanin' to make ya feel somethin' about somethin' else.

He does this a lot with colors in his book *The Great Gatsby*. He's got these colors, like gold, green, white, gray, and red, and he gives 'em all these deep meanings. Then he uses 'em to make ya remember how somethin' makes ya feel.

Take white and gray, for example. He makes 'em mean somethin' like sameness, like everything's the same. White's a bit nicer, fancier, while gray's more old and faded, ya know?

He shows ya this right from the start, with everyone wearin' white. Daisy and Jordan, they're always in white. Heck, even Nick's wearin' white to Gatsby's party! And Tom's got on a white shirt when he meets Myrtle.  The only time folks ain't wearin' white is when Nick's at Gatsby's party, and then it's all these loud, bright colors.

Fitzgerald uses these colors everywhere, like when Nick goes to work, he goes down these "white chasms" in New York.  And the names at Gatsby's party? They're all just "gray names."  Even Catherine's apartment building looks like a big white cake, all the same.

He even uses white and gray for regular folks and places. Jordan and Daisy had a "white girlhood." There are "gray cars" and "gray land" in that depressing valley of ashes.  

Fitzgerald keeps us thinkin' about these colors, buildin' up this whole feelin' for 'em. Then, when he wants ya to think somethin' ain't important, or it's just part of the crowd, he uses white or gray.

Take Daisy, for example. After he's been using these colors everywhere, he describes Daisy all in white, in her white car. Suddenly, she doesn't seem so special anymore, just like somethin' Gatsby wants, somethin' uniform, like a pretty package. 

He does this with Daisy a few more times, makin' her seem more like a pretty picture than a real person. She's got a "gray haze" around her neck, and she's wearin' white again before that big showdown with Tom and Gatsby.

Well, let me tell ya, San Diego's a pretty darn good place to grow stuff. That sunshine and mild weather? Makes for some mighty fine tomatoes, citrus, and all sorts of veggies. You got your squash, your broccoli, herbs galore, even peaches and lemons. And don't forget the berries and peppers!

Seems like folks around here are real keen on their organic eats too. There's a whole heap of folks signed up for community-supported agriculture, waiting for their share of that fresh-picked goodness. And eggs and milk? Organic all the way, folks!

A lot of these farms, they ain't just about the crops. They let you take a gander at how they do things, even go for a hike or watch the birds. Seems like a good way to make a livin' while helpin' out the environment, ya know?

Now, organic farming ain't always easy. It takes a lot more elbow grease to keep those pests and weeds at bay without all the fancy chemicals. Plus, crops sometimes don't do as well as with the regular stuff. But, it sure does do wonders for the critters and plants around here. More biodiversity, that's what they call it.

But hold on, there's more to it!  These folks makin' a go of it with wildlife in mind, they gotta do all sorts of extra work. Plantin' special cover crops, makin' sure the animals have a good place to graze, even gettin' rid of those pesky invasives.  

So, this landowner I was talkin' about, he's got a real pickle on his hands. He wants to make a decent livin' and help the critters out too. That takes some know-how and a little help, ya see.

This land he's lookin' at, it's out near Potrero, a real beautiful spot.  It's got chaparral, grassland, and oak trees, all right next to that Cleveland National Forest.  They're sayin' there's all sorts of critters livin' there, some endangered, some just hangin' on.

Been sayin' this land's been around for ages, first the Native Americans, then some ranchers and folks sellin' firewood. Back in the day, this was a homestead, so it was probably used for grazin' or choppin' wood.

Now, I found this piece of property online and figured out what kind of help this farmer might be able to get. I even found a real organic farm nearby, doin' pretty much what I'm talkin' about.

Listen, everybody knows culture matters when you're tryin' to get somethin' done.  It ain't just about what a culture is, but what it ain't, you know?  It's not like everyone in a place is the same, like sayin' all Rednecks are stubborn or all them fancy Japanese are always playin' it nice.  That's just plain dumb talk.  

What you gotta do is figure out how that culture's gonna play out in the deal you're makin'.  You see the world through your own eyes, and it's natural to compare, but you gotta go deeper than that.

Think about it like this:  when you're dealin' with folks from a different place, you gotta learn their history, their hang-ups, the things they think are important.  Don't go tryin' to change 'em, just gotta respect it.  It's like when you're on someone else's turf - you gotta play by their rules, especially if you're the one with less to offer.  Treat 'em right, show 'em respect for their ways, and you'll get further.

And it ain't just countries, you know.  Inside any big company, there's a whole culture goin' on.  Some places are all about workin' 'til you drop, others are laid back.  How they dress, how they talk, who they hire - it all tells ya somethin' about their culture.  Some companies encourage helpin' others, others are all about makin' money.  Just look around you - there's all kinds of different ways to do business.

Values are the real key though.  They're the heart of a culture, the reason everything else is the way it is.  If a culture cares about lookin' good or gettin' along, they ain't gonna embarrass their boss to win a deal.  If they're all about makin' a tough bargain, they ain't gonna cave easy.  

So, before you walk into any kinda negotiation, do your homework.  Figure out the culture, what they stand for, what makes 'em tick.  And don't forget, get to know the folks you're dealin' with on a personal level too.  That's how you really make a deal.

Dang ol' psalm talkin' about how folks say there ain't no God, right?  Well, that's what Anselm and Aquinas are tryin' to prove wrong.  They both believe in the same God, the one from the Bible.  Now, we gotta figure out whose argument makes more sense, so we're gonna pretend they're both right about God existin'. 

Anselm, he thinks we gotta look inside ourselves to find God.  He says since we can think about God, He must be real.  Kinda like, if you can picture a dang ol' redneck in a pickup truck, that means there's gotta be rednecks in pickup trucks out there, right?  Anselm's sayin' that God's gotta be real 'cause we can think about Him.  He calls it faith, I reckon.

Aquinas, he's a different kinda fella.  He thinks we can prove God exists with logic and stuff, like lookin' at the world and sayin', "Hey, this ain't just happenin' by itself, there's gotta be a reason!"  He's got five different reasons, but they all boil down to sayin' that God makes sense, ya know?

Both of 'em got some good points, but neither one of 'em really convinces me that God's gotta be real.

Alright, so there was this dude, right? Way back in the day, like 5 or 600 BC, he was born a prince. But this dude, the one they'd later call Buddha, he decided to ditch the fancy life and go all spiritual. He figured out some stuff about how the world works, and his ideas started this whole religion called Buddhism. Now, the most straight-up kind of Buddhism is called Theravada, and it's been around for about 2,500 years. Things have changed a bit since Buddha was around, you know?

Like, in Sri Lanka, these guys still do this big water-cutting ceremony every year. Monks and regular folks, they all join in, and it's kinda important to them, even though Buddha never mentioned anything about it. It's like that with a lot of stuff in Theravada Buddhism—some stuff's changed from the old days, both the little stuff and the big stuff.  The monks and the regular folks who follow Buddhism, they've had to tweak their ideas a bit over time. It's like, life changes things, ya know?

We gotta talk about some words a lot in this here story. We're gonna say things like "internal" and "external," and "hostile" and "benign." Think of it this way: "internal" means something coming from inside the Buddhist group, whether you're a monk or not. "External" means something coming from folks outside of Buddhism. "Hostile" means something bad for Buddhism, like someone trying to mess it up. "Benign" means something that's not trying to help or hurt Buddhism, but might end up doing one or the other by accident.

First things first, let's get the basics of Theravada Buddhism down. Buddhists put their faith in the "Triple Gem"—the Buddha, his teachings (the Dhamma), and the community of Buddhists (the Sangha). The Dhamma is like a big library of Buddhist writings called the "Tripitaka."  There's the Sutta Pitaka with all the Buddha's teachings, the Vinaya Pitaka with the rules for monks, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka with the deep, philosophical stuff about Buddhism.

They talk about things like Anatta (no soul), Dukkha (suffering), and Anicca (everything changes).  They think that by understanding these things, you can escape Sansara, which is like a big wheel of life, death, and being reborn over and over.  And when you get out of that wheel, you get rid of Lobha (desire), Dosa (hatred), and Moha (delusion). That's when you become enlightened.

Listen, you ever hear about how the US and Mexico used to be like cat and dog, fightin' over everything?  They were at odds for like 57 years straight!  Back in the 1840s, we even went to war with 'em over Texas and parts of the Southwest.  It was a real mess, folks.  They call it the Mexican-American War, and we kicked their butts good.  But it weren't just that one fight, see?  They kept buttin' heads over things like religion, their way of life, and all sorts of stuff.  Kinda like how neighbors might argue over a fence or somethin'. 

This ain't nothin' new, though.  Countries that live next to each other, they tend to get into it sometimes.  Look at us and Cuba, or even with Canada sometimes.  It's just how things go.  You got some folks sayin' that we've had more trouble with Mexico and Cuba than any other country.  Maybe they got a point.

Now, religion played a big part in all this.  Back then, Americans didn't like Catholics much, and Mexicans, well, they were Catholic as can be.  Just like the Cold War, where we were against Russia 'cause of their communism, it was kinda like that, but with religion instead.  It ain't easy when you got different beliefs, you know?

These two countries, they had a lot of spats back then.  Mostly about land, and bandits crossin' the border and causin' trouble.  It took both sides sendin' in the troops to finally put a stop to it.  Eventually, though, things cooled down.  Mexico started dependin' on us more and more, and we weren't so interested in takin' their land anymore.

Fifteen years ago, bam! I got hit with this sickness, outta nowhere.  Didn't even know it existed!  I was a nurse back then, ya know, figured I'd always have a job, 'cause people always get sick.  That's what everyone kept sayin' growing up.  Truth is, I always wanted to be a scientist or a writer, maybe both, but  nursing seemed like the safe bet.  Well, here I am, 46, single, broke as a joke, and can't work.  Still can't, after 15 years on disability.  Got nothin' left,  barely gettin' by.  Every day is a fight,  feelin' like I'm losin' everything I got.  Nothing's certain anymore, except I couldn't have made it this long without my family and a few good friends.  'Cause when life throws you a real curveball,  strong don't mean a darn thing.

My point is,  life throws ya curveballs, big and small.  No use tryin' to predict 'em,  and sometimes,  no matter how prepared you are,  you just need a hand.  

Now, I get it, we gotta stop relyin' so much on the government.  It's a mess, that much is clear. But wouldn't it be better if folks started lookin' out for each other again?  Help when they can, ask for help when they need it.  Rather than everyone buildin' their own little bunkers.

Those folks talkin' 'bout rugged individualism,  they forget what really built this country.  It wasn't just grit, it was folks lookin' out for each other, sharin' what they had.  Those pioneers crossing the Rockies,  they didn't make it alone.

So yeah, be prepared!  I am.  Got my disaster kit, first aid, water filters,  even plastic sheeting for the windows,  just in case. Flashlights, batteries, candles, the whole shebang.  If you can grow your own food,  can it,  do it.  Wood stove,  if you got the space.  But while you're at it,  get to know your neighbors.

Alright, so you wanna know how critters change over time, right? Like, why they get all different lookin'?  Well, it ain't simple, ya know?  It's kinda like tryin' to figure out how to build a house just by lookin' at a picture of it. We've got some smart folks tryin' to figure this out with math, like tryin' to write down the rules of how a shell grows up, ya know? They're lookin' at these ancient seashells called Prunum and tryin' to see how they changed over time.

They're usin' fancy pictures and computer programs to make models of these shells, kinda like buildin' a 3D puzzle. They wanna see what shapes are possible, like what kinda twists and turns a shell can take. Then they're gonna compare that to real shells and see how close they get.

Think of a shell like a spiral staircase windin' around. Each step is a whorl, and the center pole is the columella. Some shells get bigger faster than others, and the line between each whorl is called a suture. The biggest whorl is the one at the bottom, and all the rest are called the spire.  

Anyways, they're tryin' to figure out the rules of the game, how these shells change shape over time.  It's like tryin' to figure out how a plant grows, but with shells!

Listen, here's the deal with Indonesia.  They're doin' alright, y'know, gettin' their water and sanitation squared away like they promised.  But when it comes to takin' care of moms and babies, they're fallin' behind.  Like, really fallin' behind.

Now, they're braggin' about makin' sure more babies are born with a doctor or somethin' around,  but let me tell ya, sometimes those "doctors" are just old ladies who don't know nothin' 'bout real medicine.  And that's why so many moms end up dyin' from bleedin' out after childbirth.  It's a mess, plain and simple.

On top of that, fewer kids are gettin' help for their belly aches, and nobody seems to be lookin' after 'em after they're born.  It's like they're just lettin' these kids fend for themselves.

And don't even get me started on the C-sections.  They're doin' them way too little, especially out in the sticks.  It's like the rich folks get all the good healthcare, while everyone else is stuck with whatever they can scrounge up.

So what's the answer?  Should they just keep throwin' money at this problem with a bunch of different programs, or should they fix the whole darn healthcare system?  It's a tough call.  Programmatic approaches are easier to manage, but they can suck up all the resources and leave other parts of the system starved.  Plus,  you end up with a bunch of different groups doin' the same thing, but not talkin' to each other.  It's a recipe for disaster.

Victorian novels are known for their super detailed descriptions and their focus on the rich and fancy folks back then. But there are a couple of books from that time, Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights, that don't quite fit that mold. They're kinda spooky and a little weird, which is different from most novels from that era. This weirdness actually makes the characters more interesting, giving us a better understanding of what makes them tick.

Take this passage from Oliver Twist:

“And now, hosts of bewildering and confusing ideas came crowding on his mind. He seemed to be still walking between Sikes and Crackit, who were angrily disputing: for the very words they said, sounded in his ears; and when he caught his own attention, … he found that he was talking to them…. Suddenly he started back at the report of fire arms; and there rose into the air loud cries and shouts; lights gleamed before his eyes, and all was noise and tumult, as some unseen hand bore him hurriedly away. Through all these rapid visions, there ran an undefined, uneasy consciousness of pain, which weared and tormented him incessantly.” 
(Dickens, 220)


These books often use mystery and dream-like scenes to do this, but they do it in different ways. In Oliver Twist, these strange happenings show us what's going on inside Oliver's head, his pain, and how he sees the world around him. When Oliver gets shot, he relives it all over again in a dream-like state as he tries to find help. 

This passage shows how out of control Oliver feels.  He's overwhelmed, and his pain is constant and linked with fear, not just shock.  It makes you wonder who's really in charge of his fate, because it's definitely not him.  He doesn't even try to fight back, even when his life is on the line.  This makes you think that maybe he's starting to give up hope, like Fagin has broken him and made him accept this miserable fate.


“The day passed off – day! There was no day; it was gone as soon as come – and night came on again; night so long, and yet so short; long in it’s dreadful silence and short in it’s fleeting ours."

A couple years back, I was workin' in this after-school program, helpin' out little kids with their schoolwork. I was pretty good at English and readin', so I'd help out with whatever those kids were strugglin' with. One time, they asked me to help this little fella named Adrian, maybe in third or fourth grade. He was havin' a real tough time readin'. I mean, it was just plain weird. Some letters he'd get right, but others, he'd butcher 'em somethin' fierce.

You see, Adrian was Latino, spoke perfect English, but his readin' was all messed up. We were hittin' a wall, I mean, I didn't know what to do! Then one day, Adrian's momma came to pick him up. Now, she didn't speak a lick of English. Just Spanish. I could barely spit out a few words myself, but we managed to get by. And that's when it hit me like a ton of bricks: Adrian could read just fine, he just didn't know the English alphabet that well. 

I ain't sure if that helped him much, but I sure do hope he's doin' better now. 

I tell that story 'cause it shows ya, there's this big ol' language barrier in schools, especially here in California. It ain't always as obvious as ya think. Even if a kid speaks English good, readin' it can be a real headache.

We all know this problem exists, so what can we do about it? In Adrian's case, it was easy: tutor him in English readin', teach him the alphabet and how to pronounce things right. But for kids who barely speak English, it's a whole different ball game. There ain't just one answer, ya know? Dual language programs, mainstream immersion, private tutors, ESL classes, nothin' works all on its own. We gotta throw everything at it!

Dual language programs are a good start. Not just for Spanish speakers, but for everyone.  It's like, kids in these programs do better in school than the rest. Some folks are scared of it, think it wastes money and ain't good for everyone. That's hogwash! If we made these programs the norm, not the exception, everyone would benefit. 

But how do we do it? Make every teacher bilingual? Nah, that's crazy talk. But we could have bilingual assistants, tutors, whatever ya wanna call 'em, to help out.

Man, ever since we were little kids, folks told us there's somethin' bigger out there, somethin' we can't even wrap our heads around. Some go to church, some go to temple, some just try to figure it out on their own. A lot of us just go with what our folks taught us, but some folks, they say "heck no!", they don't believe in nothin' but what they can see right in front of 'em.  We might believe in one thing one day, then change our minds the next.  No matter what, we're all lookin' for somethin' to give our lives meaning, somethin' to light the way when things get dark.

My dad, he loved cardinals. I asked him once, sittin' on the porch, rain comin' down like crazy. We were smokin' cigarettes, my dad lookin' thin and tired, his hair gettin' sparser by the day. He just stared out at the rain, thinkin' about somethin', I guess.  I felt kinda lost, scared, and couldn't bring myself to say nothin' 'bout how much I was gonna miss him, 'cause talkin' about it would just make it all too real. So I hugged him, sat closer, and just watched the rain with him.


My dad passed away that December, just a few days after I turned 22.  They tried to help him with chemo and radiation, but it just kept him alive longer, even though he was sufferin'. I couldn't figure out what good that was doin'. What kind of God would let somethin' like that happen, I thought.  I didn't pray, 'cause I figured God had stopped listenin' to me a long time ago.

I didn't wanna watch him die. I couldn't. I wanted to remember him how he was, not how he died. Besides, I knew him better than anyone else, better than his family even. I knew he wouldn't want me standin' there watchin' him go.  So I just curled up in bed for three days, waitin' for the news. 

No one even called me.

So, this whole "Gothic Novel" thing, it's kinda like a head-scratcher.  You got this fancy name, "Gothic," but it's like sayin' somethin' that's both old and new at the same time.  This fella, Ian Watt, he says it best in his book about how Gothic novels came to be.  Folks have been talkin' smack about 'em, praisin' 'em to the heavens, sayin' they ain't got nothin' goin' on, then turnin' around and sayin' they're pure genius.  It's a real mixed bag, this Gothic stuff. 

It all started with this guy, Horace Walpole, and his book, "The Castle of Otranto."  He mixed up these old-timey stories with the newfangled novels folks were writin' back then.  He called it "A Gothic Story," and it was somethin' new, somethin' different.  Gothic novels, they got all this stuff from those old medieval plays and castles, and all those fancy traditions.  Back when Walpole wrote his book, people were already throwin' around the word "Gothic" for all sorts of things, but it usually meant somethin' old-fashioned or kinda dumb compared to all the newfangled stuff everyone thought was so much better.  But by puttin' these old Gothic ideas into a new kind of story, somethin' where you got right inside the characters' heads, somethin' new and powerful happened.  Gothic stuck around for a long time, even though it felt both old and brand new at the same time.

One big thing about Gothic is this idea of chivalry.  You know, knights and all that.  In those old days, they trained these knights to be brave, honorable, all that jazz.  Gothic writers, well, they liked that idea a lot, 'cause they felt like folks weren't so chivalrous anymore.  So they used those old knightly ideas to make the past seem better than the present.  It's like sayin', "Hey, back in the day, folks were awesome, but now everyone's messed up!"

Walpole, he wrote "The Castle of Otranto" when things were kinda crazy politically.  He was worried about the future, and maybe felt like folks had lost their way.  In his book, he shows this character, Frederic, who's supposed to be this perfect knight.  He's got all the fancy words and descriptions, like he's straight outta a medieval fairytale.  Walpole's tryin' to make you think, "Wow, back in the day, these guys were somethin' special!"

Well, lemme tell ya 'bout this here supply chain thingy.  It's like a big ol' chain, see? Starts with the customer, when they want somethin'.  Gotta get them raw materials, make the stuff, then ship it right back to the customer.  A fella named Keith Oliver, back in '82, came up with the name, said it's all about plannin', doin', and keepin' track of everything so the customer gets what they want, fast and cheap.  

There's six main parts to this chain, see: makin' it, gettin' it, keepin' track of it, where it's at, how it gets moved, and all the info about it.  Managers gotta use all these parts to make the customers happy.

First up is makin' the stuff, that's the heart of the whole thing.  Gotta figure out what to make, how much, where, and how to do it.  Look at what folks are buyin', that's your clue what they want.  Lots of talk about the market, fancy word for what people are buyin'.  Once you know what to make, gotta decide where to make it, gotta be the right place for makin' that kinda stuff good and right.  Then it's schedulin' who does what, and keepin' the machines workin'.  Don't mess this part up, it'll cost ya in the long run!

Used to work at Walmart and Target, both got all sorts of rules and booklets for everything, from how an employee's uniform should look to how to unload trucks.  Gotta have it all figured out so everyone knows what they're doin'.

Then comes gettin' the stuff, see, gotta figure out where to get all the parts and stuff to make the product.  You might have different places makin' different parts, gotta figure out who's best for what.  Sometimes you gotta hire other companies to help, that's callin' it "outsourcing".  Doin' this makes things faster and cheaper, but do it right, or you'll end up payin' more.

Well, lemme tell ya somethin'. This here Ellen Page, she's a pretty little thing, ain't she?  She was standin' on a street corner, holidin' up this sign, right? And it said somethin' real messed up: "Hitler is alive in Burma!"  Now, Burma, that's a place way over yonder, kinda like the wild west, but with more temples and less tumbleweeds. They got this bunch of tough guys runnin' things, callin' themselves the junta, and they ain't afraid to use force if folks start gettin' uppity.  

A few years back, these monks, they started protestin', wearin' their saffron robes, lookin' all peaceful and stuff. But the junta, they didn't like it. They started crackin' down hard, beatin' folks up, even killin' some. It was a real mess. They even locked up some fellas just for tryin' to take pictures of what was goin' on. 

Now, this ain't the first time somethin' like this has happened.  Governments, they always want to be in charge, ain't they?   Like those Roman emperors, thinkin' they were gods.  And don't even get me started on those Japanese emperors, thinkin' they're gods too! And let's not forget ol' George W. Bush, talkin' to that Ted Haggard fella, leader of the Dumb Folks Club.  

We had that Tiananmen Square thing back in the day, where a bunch of folks got together, and the Chinese government, well, let's just say they didn't handle it real well. And then there was that Rwanda mess, where they went and killed a whole bunch of people just 'cause they were different. And who can forget ol' Hitler, with his whole "Final Solution" thing?

It's enough to make a fella want to move to Mars, ain't it?

Duke Ellington was a jazz legend, and one reason why is he stuck around so long and kept making new music. He really knew how to shape his band, making 'em sound like a real family. 

Now, you might not hear Ellington playing the piano a whole lot in some of his songs, but he was a whiz at writing music that was both fancy and deep. He'd give his guys room to show off their skills, letting 'em improvise, but he also knew how to write tight sections where everyone had to play just right.  He was like a conductor, makin' sure every instrument sounded good together,  creating somethin' fresh and new every time. Because of this, he wrote some of the best jazz music ever.

This one music book says he was always tryin' new things, like using voices as instruments. Check out "Creole Love Call", where he uses a voice to add some texture to the music without actually singin' any words.  He was always findin' ways to make his musicians shine, and this song shows it. It's a slow blues song where the voice and the woodwinds take turns talkin' to each other. The trumpet player does some fancy stuff, the clarinet player soars high, and the whole band comes together in the end. It's a real showstopper, and you can hear how much Ellington cared about makin' each part sound perfect.

He did the same thing in another song called "Hot and Bothered". He had a trumpet player named "Bubber" and a singer named Baby Cox, and they'd go back and forth, makin' their voices and instruments sound like one. It was like a conversation, kinda funny and kinda soulful. Then there's "It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing)", where he uses a trombone player named "Tricky Sam" to start the song. This guy was a regular in Ellington's band, and he played that trombone like nobody's business.

She'd always felt like somethin' was missin', like there was a hole in her life that nothin' seemed to fill. This need started when she was about 14, just a young'un, and it was still there three years later, at 17. By then, she figured out she wanted someone, not some material thing.  But she just wasn't interested in any fellas. Some tried to court her, makin' all them awkward moves, but nobody really caught her eye. She wondered about herself a lot, tryin' to figure out why this was happenin' to her.  She thought about it for a few years, tryin' to come up with answers, but nothin' really stuck. So she just kept on livin', always wonderin' about what she really wanted.

Her days at home were usually pretty peaceful.  Her folks were good, quiet folks.  They never fought, and strangely enough, they hardly ever argued with her either. The only time they ever clashed was when she tried to show 'em she was her own person. She was the daughter of two calm souls, but she sure did bring the energy with her big, fun personality. She was a likeable gal, and that personality sure didn't hurt.

But today wasn't a calm day.  She was wanderin' around the house, lookin' for somethin' to inspire her, when she heard a little scream from the kitchen. It was her mama's voice, and it sounded scared. She ran in, panic settin' in, "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!"  

Her mama was on the floor, holdin' herself, lettin' out little "Ow"s every time she breathed. Her daughter rushed to her side, puttin' a hand on her. "Ouch... sweety, I... need you to take me to... the hospital." Her words were rushed and strained. Her daughter knew right then, her mama was hurt bad.  "Okay, Mom, just tell me where I can pick you up." 

Her mama pointed her hand, and her daughter, grateful she'd taken those strength trainin' classes, scooped her mama up and carried her to the car. She laid her down in the back, and they drove off.

The hospital smelled like medicine and sickness, kinda scary, but she wasn't feelin' that. She was too busy worryin' about her mama. She rushed her inside and shouted for help.  A few worried faces gathered around, someone grabbed a gurney and laid mama down on it. They took her away, and her daughter sat there, waitin' and worryin'.

Turns out, her mama had fallen off a step stool while tryin' to reach a vase from the top shelf.

Y'all know how they talk about that "Mediterranean Diet"?  Well, this study wanted to see if eatin' like folks in the Mediterranean really keeps your ticker tickin' strong.  

They call it the "aMed diet" - it's like the Mediterranean Diet's cousin, but with more plants, good fats, and fish.  Less of that red meat and greasy stuff, ya know?  And a little wine ain't gonna hurt ya, neither.

Now, folks have been sayin' for a while that eatin' this way keeps ya outta the hospital, but nobody really looked at strokes before.  This study followed a bunch of nurses for 20 years -  over 70,000 of 'em! -  and they asked 'em about what they ate every few years.  They wanted to see if the nurses who ate more like folks in the Mediterranean had fewer heart attacks and strokes.

Turns out, they did!  The nurses who ate the healthiest, they had less heart problems and strokes compared to the others. It's like a magic shield against those nasty heart attacks and strokes.

You know, back in 2007, America took a real nosedive. Jobs went poof, houses weren't worth nothin', and even the big ol' companies were goin' belly up. This mess, it's still hangin' around like a bad smell, so we gotta figure out what went wrong, right? Well, lemme tell ya, it all started with some real dumb decisions made by folks in these fancy suits in Washington. They were pressurin' banks and businesses to hand out loans to folks who couldn't afford 'em, like givin' candy to a bunch of sugar-crazed kids. Meanwhile, these government fellas, Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, they were gettin' pressured to bundle up all these bad loans and sell 'em off like hotcakes. When folks started missin' their payments, the whole thing went kablooey. Banks were broke, folks lost their homes, and the whole darn economy went south faster than a greased pig at a county fair.

See, this whole mess started back in 1999, when Bill Clinton was still in the White House. He was lookin' to get re-elected, so he loosened up the rules on loans, thinkin' he could buy himself another term. Well, bless his heart, he didn't see the trouble comin'.  A fella named Steven Holmes over at the New York Times, he saw right through it. He was sayin' back then that Fannie Mae, the big mortgage bank, was gettin' pushed too hard to make loans to folks who couldn't afford 'em. He even said it might lead to another financial disaster like what happened in the 80s with the savings and loans.  Boy, was he right!

They started makin' these fancy new mortgages, with adjustable rates and all sorts of bells and whistles.  Folks were buyin' houses faster than you can say "open house," and nobody thought nothin' of it.  But it was all a big ol' bubble, just waitin' to burst. And burst it did! When the housing market crashed, all those fancy mortgages went south, and the whole financial system went with 'em.  Big banks were in trouble, folks were losin' their homes, and the economy was tankin' faster than a greased pig at a county fair.

Ok, so you're writin' a story, right? And you gotta get all the backstory out there, the kinda stuff that tells folks who these characters are and what's goin' on.  That's what folks call exposition, I reckon. But lemme tell ya, too much exposition can make your story about as exciting as a bowl of dry cereal. 

It's like when you're talkin' to your buddy and just keepin' on blabbin' about your day, and he's just lookin' at you like, "Can we get to the good part already?"  

You see, folks like to see things happen, not just hear about 'em. Instead of sayin' "This fella was a real heartbreaker, he had a whole bunch of girlfriends," show 'em!  Let 'em see him charm the socks off some dame or make a gal blush with a wink. 

Same goes for that gal who lost her man.  Instead of just sayin' she was heartbroken, show her cryin' her eyes out, or maybe picturing him in her mind, or even gettin' back into the swing of things with a new hobby.

It's all about makin' 'em feel somethin', ya know?  You gotta give 'em somethin' to sink their teeth into.

Well, lemme tell ya 'bout these newscasts I watched from Columbus, Ohio. I caught the NBC 4 one this mornin', August 13th, 2011.  Their big story was 'bout this fella in Ashley, Ohio, named Shad Hostettler who stabbed his wife - didn't say her name though. They showed his picture, and lemme tell ya, the guy looked like pure evil! They only spent a couple minutes on it, 'cause it was still unfoldin', but they said he stabbed her a whole bunch and got busted. Seems like they covered it just right.

Then they had a story 'bout a young fella, Travis Buyers, 18 years old, shot in the Sharon Woods area.  He was real bad off, no arrests yet, SWAT team lookin' into it. Seemed kinda rushed, and it made me think, ya know, maybe it's 'cause he was a black man or livin' in a black neighborhood. I've noticed for years, the media don't give minorities the same attention when they're hurt. If it's a white kid or grown-up, they go crazy, but a minority, they're lucky to even get a mention.

Next up was a story about a .22 bullet hittin' a Med-Flight chopper. They figured out where it happened and everything. Crime Stoppers was offerin' five grand for any info leadin' to the shooter.

Then they threw in a quick one 'bout rain and thunderstorms comin' on Saturday. They said it'd be in the eighties all weekend.  They kept it short, probably to get ya hooked for more.

They also had a robbery at a UDF on Clime Road. Said the guy was black, wearin' a hoodie, about six foot tall and one hundred and fifty pounds.  They kept hammerin' on 'bout him bein' black and how dark he was. Seemed kinda strange to me.

Finally, they talked 'bout this Rene Rodriguez, some drug kingpin from Texas.  Convicted of sendin' tons of weed to Ohio.  Instead of sayin' he got twenty-five years, they said "300 months."  Maybe they thought that sounded scarier or somethin'.  They also mentioned he was Hispanic, but that didn't really seem important to the story.

Brothers, man, they're somethin' else.  Ya know, there's this crazy bond between 'em, like nothin' else. It's filled with all kinds of stuff: love, pride, jealousy, even anger sometimes.  Brothers get each other, more than anyone else, like lookin' in a mirror. You see yourself in 'em, the good and the bad. And when things get tough, that bond really shows its true colors, for better or worse.  It's a heavy thing, that bond, and it comes with a price.  

Ya gotta understand, when you look at your brother, you see yourself, not how folks see you, but the real you.  What you do, and what happens because of it, that's your true character. This story, "The Scarlet Ibis", it's all about that, about these two brothers and all the crazy stuff they feel for each other.

This story takes place in a beautiful, lush place, but these boys, they're on a trip that ain't gonna end well. There's this big clash between disappointment and pride, and in the end, only one brother makes it out alive. The story shows you the brother's feelings through the main character, Doodle, and how he acts.  It's like lookin' into his head, seein' how he feels about everything, and how that shapes his actions.

This brother, he's all about pride, from the moment he and Doodle first head out together, right up to that last, bad trip. He wanted a brother he could teach all sorts of things to, like how to hold his breath, run, jump, climb trees, all that.  He wanted someone to race with, someone to hang out with. But Doodle, he was born different, with a weak heart.  It was like his dreams were crushed right there. The poor kid was never gonna be able to do any of that stuff. This brother, he even thought about smotherin' Doodle, can you believe it? That's some dark stuff. But then Doodle smiles at him, and his heart melts.  See, deep down, he loved his brother, even if he didn't always show it.

Now listen up, cuz the brain is a right tricky thing, kinda like tryin' to figure out how a dang tractor works. Back in the day, folks thought it was like a wax tablet, then a scroll, then a book. Nowadays, they say it's like a computer. But just remember, these ol' sayings ain't always right, kinda like sayin' a 2x4 is gonna solve all your problems.

So here's the deal: you got all these senses, right? They're like little spies, tellin' your brain about the world - touchin' stuff, hearin' noises, seein' colors. Your brain takes all that info and shuffles it around, makin' sense of it all. It's like buildin' a picture outta jigsaw pieces, startin' with the little bits and then puttin' 'em together to see the whole thing. Sometimes it's like, "Hey, that's a box!" and other times it's like, "Hold on, is that a box or a hole?"  Your brain's always guessin' and chewin' on things.

Now your brain's got this filter, kinda like a bouncer at a club. It decides what's important and what can be tossed aside. You see a whole bunch of blades of grass, but your brain's like, "Nah, ain't worth payin' attention to those." But if someone says your name, bam! Your brain's all ears.

To remember stuff, your brain's got these storerooms: short-term memory, where things hang out for a bit, and long-term memory, where things stick around for good. It's like puttin' stuff in a filing cabinet, but your brain does it all with electricity and chemicals, which is way more complicated than me tryin' to organize my toolshed.

Now, folks try to figure out how all this knowledge is organized in your brain, kinda like tryin' to map out a big ol' maze. Some say it's like a web, where ideas are connected to each other. And that makes sense, cuz think about it - "chair" is connected to "table," "table" is connected to "wood," and so on.  It's all tangled up, just like life itself!

Now listen, this Huxley fella, he's got somethin' to say about all this fancy tech and the whole money-grubbin' system we got goin' on.  He wrote this book, "Brave New World," and it's a real downer. These people, they ain't got no individuality. They're all about bein' part of the crowd and gettin' their kicks right now, no matter what. They're just pawns in a game played by this big-shot World Controller. 

See, this book, it makes ya think about all that Marxist stuff, ya know, the class struggle and all that. Huxley was suspicious about all this progress and how it messes with regular folks.  He's talkin' about how the rich folks keep the poor folks dumb and happy,  makin' 'em think they're doin' alright when they ain't.  It's like they're hypnotized into just buyin' and buyin', never questionin' nothin'.

The World Controller, he's like the big boss man, pullin' all the strings. He makes sure the folks are happy, but only in a shallow way.  They got all this stuff, but no real connection to each other.  It's all about appearances and instant gratification.

And the people, they're just puppets. They don't even know they're bein' controlled. They just go along with it, thinkin' they're livin' the good life.  

It's kinda like what Marx said about the rich guys exploitin' the poor guys.  They keep 'em busy with distractions, makin' 'em think they're better off than they really are.  

Huxley's book is a warning, y'know? He's sayin' that if we keep goin' down this path, we're gonna lose our freedom and our humanity. We gotta wake up and see what's really goin' on before it's too late.

Well, I've been slummin' it here at University Park for about two and a half years now, four and a half semesters if you wanna get technical. Let me tell ya, gettin' around this campus is a real pain in the neck, and I ain't talkin' about the dang squirrels! My freshman year, they stuck me in one of those East Halls dorms,  like way out east, past the football stadium and that big ol' Bryce Jordan Center.  To get to my classes, man, you'd think I was crossin' the Sahara Desert!  Willard building, right smack in the middle of campus, felt like it was a hundred miles away. Walkin' there in the rain, which happens more often than not in State College,  could take you 25 minutes, easy. I talked to this old grad, not much older than me, and he told me those East Halls used to be way out in the boonies, surrounded by nothin' but empty land. Now it's all fancy sports fields, new buildings like that new Creamery and the health center, and apartments everywhere.  Seems like they're buildin' somethin' new every day, but nothin' to help us get around!

Now, what's the answer to this transportation mess?  A bicycle, that's what!  But it ain't just about havin' a bike, ya know?  Students gotta use 'em, and the campus needs to be built with bikes in mind.

I was talkin' to my buddy, he got back into ridin' after takin' a break for a few years. He said, "Forget about it, bikes are the only way to go!  It ain't cool to ride bikes anymore, but it's the dang fastest way to get around." Besides bein' good for ya, it's the most efficient way to travel. A bowl of oatmeal and a little peddlin' and you can go 30 miles, easy.  I live off campus now, just as far from the center of campus as some dorms, and the best decision I made all year was buyin' a bike.  I take classes in Thomas building, a good 25-minute walk from my house.  On a bike, I can get there in 5 minutes flat if I pedal like a madman.

The only problem is, Pollock Road, the shortcut to Thomas, ain't always the easiest ride, bike or not.  Walkin' ain't bad, but I'm too busy for that. Without my bike, walkin' is my only option, and that's a whole lotta time wasted.

Culture plays a significant role in any negotiation. Culture can be defined as much by what it is not as what it actually is and what it signifies. Culture is not homogenous, nor is it a specific thing. It is also not singular or uniform. Statements such as “all Russians are stubborn” or “all Japanese are accommodating,” are inherently broad and overly simplistic. While the understanding of a culture’s generalizations are appropriate, it is much more productive to a negotiator to understand the significance of a culture to the matter at hand, and how that culture’s attitude can and will affect the table talks. When one approaches a foreign culture, one experiences it in a way that is relatable to his own culture, and comparisons necessarily arise. 

Attempting to understand a foreign culture or mindset can involve anything from studying its history to realizing its prejudices. Rather than judging or attempting to change a culture, one must simply accept it for what it is, and work within its boundaries, especially within the scope of negotiation, and most especially if one comes to the table with a weaker bargaining position. Likewise, if a negotiator finds himself on “away” territory, a respect for traditions and beliefs can only help in getting over any cultural barriers and move the negotiation forward.

It is important to note that culture does not necessarily limit itself to a national/international dichotomy. Most companies within a given nation establish their own corporate culture. For instance, a corporate culture might emphasize long hours in the office or a more relaxed schedule. Evidence of a corporate culture can be seen in employee dress codes, in communication style (direct v. indirect communication, delegation of duties), and hiring practices. Some companies encourage philanthropy at any level from employees, others restrict it to “company approved” charities or fundraisers. One need only look at the differences in American corporate culture from company to company (and indeed, intra-company diversity exists even from region to region, urban to suburban environments included) to appreciate the diversity of thought that can reside within a particular societal culture. Certain cultures are not nearly as stratified as American culture, and may appear more uniform to an outsider, but a similar exterior is simply a sign to dig deeper. 

Values are even more important to understand, because they provide the why of a culture. If saving face or communal harmony are valued within a culture, it is certain that a negotiator will not publicly shame his company or his superior in order to succeed at the negotiation table. Likewise, a negotiator from a culture which gives greater weight to a hard-driven bargain will not necessarily be driven to settle at the earliest opportunity. Taking these generalities into consideration is important before one gets to the negotiating table. However, a negotiator is well-served to learn something about his opponent on a personal level in order to make the negotiation effective.

“The fool hath said in his heart, ‘There is no God.’” The preceding quotation is seen first in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible, and is found at the beginning of St. Anselm’s argument regarding the existence of God. This belief seems to also be held by the other author whom we will be discussing, Thomas Aquinas. Because each of their arguments is in defense of the same concept, and our challenge is to determine who’s is the better of the two, we must, for sake of brevity, begin with the presumption that they are both correct in their belief in the existence of God, specifically the God of the Bible. To allow for a God-type figure that may not resemble the one in whom our two authors believe would not permit us to appropriately compare their two arguments, as they are essentially in defense of one specific concept of God. That being said, I would suggest that while each of them brings up valid points, neither truly provides a holistic basis for belief in God.
	To illustrate this point, we will first examine the basic argument of St. Anselm. Anselm’s passage reflects a path of gaining understanding through faith, looking within one’s self to find proof of God. He explains that because God exists within our understanding, we cannot effectively conceive his nonexistence. While this concept, when spelled out in his terminology, is a bit tedious and at times unclear, the basic gist of it is that the proof for God lies within one’s own mind. St. Anselm is suggesting to us that we needn’t go beyond the confines of our own soul to find truth about God, but that the existence of this being is found to be true simply by examining that which we inherently know to be true within our own minds. Foreign evidence is presumably unnecessary. This concept of accepting that for which there is not an irrefutable body of empirical evidence is often referred to within Christian texts as faith.
	This idea is very different from that held by St. Thomas Aquinas. Aquinas instead suggests that the existence of God can be proven entirely through reason and empirical evidence, with no need for faith of any kind. Such an idea would be beneficial in evangelism, an important element of Christianity, because it would enable the recruiting of new converts without any dependency upon their willingness to accept something that cannot be proven. They could instead be persuaded by logic alone. St. Thomas elaborates on five different logical arguments supporting the existence of God: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. In each he essentially demonstrates that the proof of God lies in the logical necessity for God. If you are told that that you are missing one puzzle piece, and assemble the rest of the puzzle, logic dictates that you can know of the features and the existence of the missing piece without having to see it.

Many authors use different ways to give their readers a certain feeling or attitude toward
important subjects. Some of these techniques are more effective than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald uses
many of these different techniques in his novel The Great Gatsby. Sometimes, Fitzgerald pairs an
adjective and a noun together that do not usually fit that way to give readers a certain aura around a
subject. Other times, he applies meaning to a symbol, and then uses it for this same purpose.
Fitzgerald uses this last technique with many colors, including gold, green, white/gray and red/pink. In
his novel The Great Gatsby F. Scott Fitzgerald builds up meaning for colors, namely white/gray and
red/pink then later uses that meaning to give readers a certain reminder of a feeling around an
important object.
The meaning Fitzgerald builds up and uses for white/gray is uniformity, with white being a bit
nicer and higher class and gray being more older and faded. Fitzgerald sets up this meaning in the
beginning of the novel with constant uses of both. Daisy and Jordan are constantly “in white” (8)—in
fact, everyone is always wearing white: Nick wears “white flannels” (41) to Gatsby’s party, Tom wears
a “white shirt” (36) when he meets Myrtle, and Catherine is “powdered milky white” (30). In fact, the
only time people are not wearing white is when Nick is getting his impressions of Gatsby’s party: “the
halls... are gaudy with primary colors” (40). Fitzgerald further defines these two colors in coloring
many common, unimportant subjects these colors: as Nick goes to work, he goes “down the white
chasms of lower New York” (56), the names of people at Gatsby’s parties are now “gray names” (61)
on Nick’s timetable, Catherine’s apartment is “one slice in a long white cake of apartment-houses”—
uniformity (28). He also describes plain or common people or places as white or gray: Jordan and
Daisy had a “white girlhood” (19) together, there are “gray cars” and “gray land” (23) in the valley of
ashes, the “Italian child” in the railroad is “gray” (26), and the dog-seller is “a gray old man” (27).
After Fitzgerald adds enough meaning to white/gray, he uses them to signify unimportance or
uniformity to certain subjects. This using colors to show readers something first starts with Daisy.
After a long time without any significant use of either of these colors, Fitzgerald comes out describing
Daisy as “dressed in white” in “a little white roadster”; readers begin to see Daisy as less of a character,
more like just a uniform addition, something that Gatsby wants and longs for (74). Fitzgerald uses
more of this technique around Daisy to give this impression of Daisy being a more uniform addition,
for example, there is a “gray haze of Daisy’s fur collar” (18), and she is again in a “white” (115) dress
before Tom and Gatsby’s encounter.

San Diego County is very agriculturally productive, thanks to a mild, sunny climate. Common crops include: tomatoes, citrus, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There is a substantial market for organic community supported agriculture food in the San Diego area, with many local organizations having lengthy waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also popular. Many organic farms also provide tours of their agricultural operations as well as access for hiking, birdwatching, and other recreational activities. This is the type of operation that would allow the landowner to gain the benefits of government programs while improving habitat, thus allowing recreational use and creating an opportunity for farm tours and other programs for making money or for educational purposes.  
	In addition to filling a potentially lucrative niche market, the benefits of organic farming often include greater biodiversity in plants and wildlife in the area thanks to a lack of chemicals in the soil and water. However, organic farming has greater costs than conventional farming in some ways. It requires more intensive labor and management to remove pests and weeds and fertilize the soil without chemicals, and losses are often greater than with conventional methods, while a small organic farm also lacks the efficiency of scale of large operations. Practices not related to organic farming but beneficial to wildlife may also incur greater labor costs, including planting cover crops, strategic grazing rotation, invasive species removal, and active management of plant growth to provide specific conditions such as edge habitat or patches of open ground. Thus, there are many reasons why the landowner in this example might seek financial help or expertise in maximizing both profits and habitat quality.  
The land chosen for this scenario is a parcel adjacent to the town of Potrero, in unincorporated San Diego County, California. It is 160 acres of chaparral, nonnative Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland next to to the Cleveland National Forest. It lies in the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan. The plan is still being reviewed, but presently considers over a hundred species of plants and animals. Many are endangered, such as the Stephens' kangaroo rat, the mountain yellow-legged frog, several species of butterfly, and the California gnatcatcher; others are declining and may soon be listed, such as burrowing owls.
	This area was inhabited by Native Americans for untold centuries and was then settled by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800's. This piece of land was part of an original homestead patent and so was probably used for grazing and/or wood production for many of the intervening decades.
	 chose a piece of property from a real estate website and researched available government programs to see what options a small farmer might realistically have for mitigating costs and preserving wildlife-friendly operations.  As a model of what somebody farming this land might attempt to achieve, I located an organic farm in the same area.

There is a bond between brothers; an unbreakable, irrevocable bond. Within that bond lie many emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty, just to name a few. Brothers understand one another, far more than anyone else with that kind of bond, and they can only see themselves when looking at their brother. It is when a situation is at its most dire when the true nature of this bond shines through, be it good or evil. When these emotions become clear, they carry with them great a cost. Part of understanding the emotions born of this fraternal link is dealing with the consequences that they bring. When one can look a brother in the eye and see within that person their own reflection, they see themselves not as others see them, but as they truly are. In their actions and the consequences of those actions is where their true character lies.  In “The Scarlet Ibis”, two brothers explore this theme, and all of the raging emotions that accompany it. Throughout a lush, vividly described landscape, these two boys set out on a futile journey. Bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride in the climactic scene, and only one brother escapes with his life. The theme is expressed through direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions with each other, as well as through the narrator’s point of view, which communicates the complex feelings experienced by the protagonist and his view of the world around him, both of which are heavy influences on his actions.
	The protagonist’s actions can all be summed up by one key emotion: pride. From the time he and his little brother, Doodle, first go out together, to their final, fateful excursion, the protagonist feels resentment towards Doodle. He had wanted a brother whom he could teach all of his worldly skills, like “…holding my breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp…” He wanted a brother who could fill the role of “…someone to race to Horsehead Landing…and someone to perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn…” Obviously these things are impossible, given Doodle’s condition. Doodle was born with an extremely weak heart, making in unlikely he would even survive. Even then, it was nearly impossible that he would ever participate in vigorous physical activity. What a blow to the young protagonist, his head filled with wild fantasies, to have all of those dreams crushed in an instant. In fact, he is even shown to bear some anger towards the small child, as he recalls beginning to contemplate killing him by suffocating him with a pillow. What kind of child would have the presence of mind to consider infanticide? However, his heart melts when the small child smiles at him. Such a simple act gave the protagonist such hope! This shows that his conviction probably was not very strong. In the back of his mind, he had an instinctive love for his brother.

The human brain is a complicated, creative information-processing system. As technology advanced from primitive to modern, the metaphors used to describe the brain also advanced. Initially, it was compared to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and most recently, to a computer. As you learn about the brain, keep in mind that the usefulness of these metaphors is limited and can lead to erroneous conclusions.
Information processing starts with input from the sensory organs, which transform physical stimuli such as touch, heat, sound waves, or photons of light into electrochemical signals. The sensory information is repeatedly transformed by the algorithms of the brain in both bottom-up and top-down processing. For example, when looking at a picture of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing puts together very simple information such as color, orientation, and where the borders of the object are – where the color changes significantly over a short space – to decide that you are seeing a box. Top-down processing uses the decisions made at some steps of the bottom-up process to speed up your recognition of the box. Top-down processing in this example might help you identify the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the white background.
Once information is processed to a degree, an attention filter decides how important the signal is and which cognitive processes it should be made available to. For example, although your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. In contrast, you might pick out your name, even when spoken in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and the results of processing are modulated by attention repeatedly.
In order for the brain to process information, it must first be stored. There are multiple types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term. First, information is encoded. There are types of encoding specific to each type of sensory stimuli. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally, referring to what the printed word looks like, phonemically, referring to what the word sounds like, or semantically, referring to what the word means. Once information is stored, it must be maintained. Some animal studies suggest that working memory, which stores information for roughly 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through a particular series of neurons for a short period of time. Information in long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained in the structure of certain types of proteins.
There are numerous models of how the knowledge is organized in the brain, some based on the way human subjects retrieve memories, others based on computer science, and others based on neurophysiology. The semantic network model states that there are nodes representing concepts, and that the nodes are linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, “chair” might be linked to “table,” which can be linked to “wooden,” and so forth.

In 2007, the United States of America fell into a crushing financial crisis. Unemployment increased, the housing market crashed, and many of America’s largest and most important corportations were left in ruin. This recession persists today, so we must ask the question: how did this crisis occur, and how can we stop it? In short, the financial crisis was created by selfish and naïve political decision-making that pressured banks and firms into issuing sub-prime loans into an already immature and unsufficient financial infrastructure. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to underwite and repackage these mortgages into CDO’s and CDS’. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, the banks were short on capital reserve and transferred this chaos onto the repacked mortgages that they had sold, and on to the rest of the economy.
	The financial crisis had its roots in 1999 of the Clinton era, as the President was aiming for a second term in office. He sought to extend his presidential tenure by augmenting his popularity. To accomplish this the Clinton administration relaxed lending restrictions, which helped to set the grim stage for the sub-prime crisis seven years later.  Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported in 1999, “Fannie Mae, the nation's biggest underwriter of home mortgages, has been under increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans among low and moderate income people and felt pressure from stock holders to maintain its phenomenal growth in profits.” Holmes would go on to correctly foresee the consequences of these actions: “But the government-subsidized corporation may run into trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As detailed in the introduction, and as Holmes foresaw, ill-advised lending would certainly lead to the meltdown of the economy.
	Many factors combined to throw the economy into tailspin, one of which was the new and complex structure of mortgages. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDO’s) were all used extensively in the years leading up to the crisis, and only served to intertwine more sectors of the economy into the housing market. This led to U.S. households, and financial markets in general, to overleverage themselves in the housing market, leaving them extremely vulnerable to even small changes in price. 
	Indeed, the housing bubble burst, and the financial institutions that had bought these mortgage-backed securities were spited. The top five U.S. investment banks all together reported $4.1 trillion dollars of mortgage debts in 2007, which accounted for about 30% of the USA’s GDP. In the end, Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold exceptionally cheap, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks subjected to intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie were $5 trillion in mortgage debt, and were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition.  That place in your story where you stretch your little writer's wings and take flight, astounding one and all with your magnetic, nay magical prose.  Or the part where your readers fall asleep and/or hit the "Back" button while cursing your name.  Dr. Merlin has been known to shout at her monitor when she finds herself in the middle of Too Much Information, and not even in the fun way.

Exposition is not your friend.

My gentle readers already know the basic writing tip, "Show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin still stumbles into long passages of text where nothing happens, or worse, too much.  Exposition is the little devil sitting on your shoulder that says to get the history out of the way to get to the good parts (not to be confused with the devil sitting on the other shoulder urging the author to tell her audience every single detail of the childhoods of each character).

Exposition means telling the audience what happened, typically in simple prose.  In film, the exposition happens when one character tells another a core-dump of information ala "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner."  In fiction, the author's doing the telling.

An example is in order.  As you are reading a story, you are told that the heroine met her beloved at such a place and time, that they were married in a gala fashion, and that her husband was murdered in front of her eyes.  You would not expect this entire sequence to take two pages, during which time both he and she only get two lines of dialogue each.  You would expect the author to spend some time on the husband's character, evidencing by his speech and manner how deeply he loves his wife, and you would equally expect the heroine to show through big and small ways how much his presence in her life changed and enriched her (especially if the story were to tell you flat out later that this was the case).  A proper introduction to the husband's character would allow you to become emotionally involved with his fate and would give you insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, how deep their bond was, clues about her thoughts and beliefs and dreams as reflected through the prism of his eyes, and so on.  You would mourn his death with her, and so grow more connected to the heroine herself.

In short, you would expect meat on the simple bone of the storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to provide that meat.  (*looks at metaphor, sighs, plunges onward*)  Sometimes it is tempting to rush past certain things.  Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he used to be in the Air Force, and he's the night manager of a gas station now, and he was married twice, no kids, likes to go fishing on the weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station someday and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I watched two newscast’s from Columbus, Ohio. The first one that was “live” was NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). The lead story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio who had stabbed his wife, it did not state her name however his name was Shad Hostettler. They showed his mug shot and he looked like pure evil. They devoted only about two minutes to this story as it was developing. The only details they provide he had stabbed her multiple times and had been arrested. I think they spent an appropriate amount of time on this story. 
	The second story was about an early morning shooting of Travis Buyers, 18. He was shot in the Sharon Woods area and had been critically injured; there had been no arrests made at the time or any suspects. The SWAT Team was investigating the crime. This story seemed to be short, and I believe that might have been due to the fact this was a “black” man or a black neighborhood. I noticed (and have for years) that minorities are glossed over when they are a victim of a crime. If say a “white” child or adult is kidnapped or missing or a victim of a crime the media goes nuts; but if a minority person it’s lucky if it is even mentioned. 
	The next story was about the gunshot hole that had been found in the Med-Flight helicopter. Details were given about where they thought the incident happened.
