Complicating matters,‭ ‬most if not all genres—rap,‭ ‬rock,‭ ‬country,‭ ‬jazz,‭ ‬folk,‭ ‬just to name a few—have spawned multiple sub and sub-sub genres within their domain.  Arguably the sub-genre of Heavy Metal rock has become one of the most diverse and expressive genres of all popular music in the past‭ ‬40‭ ‬years. It is expressive because it displays a wide range of emotions,‭ ‬although they tend to lean toward the darker side of the spectrum. It is diverse in that quite soon after the beginnings of the genre,‭ ‬people started to realize that it had real flexibility and started to take advantage of it to create their own sub-genre,‭ ‬which then was followed by sub-sub-genres,‭ ‬and the chain continues until today. 

Today we have reached a point in the heavy metal movement where there are so many niches of groups that it is hard to determine what exactly heavy metal is. It has grown to incorporate so many themes from other genres,‭ ‬but like everything else,‭ ‬it spawned from somewhere. In order to properly understand the metal music that exists everywhere today,‭ ‬one must first understand what the metal movement is,‭ ‬and why it’s a movement rather than just a genre.

‎	‏Metal is,‭ ‬in many ways,‭ ‬a movement defined by darkness. Metal can be considered a‭ “‬music of more‭”—‬more bass,‭ ‬more volume,‭ ‬more violence,‭ ‬more theatricality. Less primitivism,‭ ‬more chops‭; ‬people in metal bands really know how to play their instrument,‭ ‬and it comes through in the music. Metal is also—although it may not come as a surprise—a movement that is heavily drug induced. There was a psychedelic drug boom in the mid-70‭’‬s that led to people getting crazier,‭ ‬leading to them to make crazy,‭ ‬other-worldly records,‭ ‬using the drugs as a scapegoat for their creation. It possesses many dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities,‭ ‬which was very new to the music scene because a large amount of popular music had qualities that weren’t true to the darker side of the emotional spectrum. Also,‭ ‬later generations of metal have taken some of their influence from the dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities that were so present in the Romantic Era. Lyrics such as the following express the darkness that is such a staple of the movement:‭ (‬Byrne‭)‬


	
These lyrics from Helter Skelter display the darker side of the Beatles. It exhibits an up and down,‭ ‬supposedly that of drugs. This song is considered by some to be one of the first Heavy Metal songs. It was a response to a Rolling Stones song that was also on the heavier,‭ ‬darker side. The Beatles wanted to prove that they could be just as heavy as the Stones,‭ ‬so they put that song on‭ ‬The White Album.

A few decades before the Surrealist artists began painting their dreamlike works, the artist Henri Rousseau was carefully crafting his own dreams, literally and figuratively. The Dream, a 1910 painting by the famous Post-Impressionist artist, represents not only a woman in awe at the wonders of the land she visits within a dream, but also Rousseau’s own personal dreams and goals as a painter. Since beginning his work, he dreamed of recognition, acceptance, and praise by other artists and art lovers, and found that he was faced with a difficult internal dilemma to achieve this aspiration. The Dream is Henri Rousseau’s work that best reflects his career-long internal struggle: to either conform to or mimic certain styles of painting in order to be accepted by the critical art world he so adored, or to allow himself to be creatively independent and unique, leaving his own path as he went.
Before one can analyze The Dream through this perspective, one must first be somewhat familiar with Rousseau’s biographical story. Henri Rousseau was born on May 21, 1844, in the town of Laval in northwest France. His father was a tinsmith and hardware dealer who “enjoyed bourgeois prosperity” (Shattuck 47). Growing up, he received no formal training in the arts; instead, he was employed until the age of forty working for France as a gabelou, or employee of the municipal toll service, although he received the misnomer sobriquet of douanier, a customs inspector (Shattuck 46). The death of his first wife, Clémence, which followed the deaths of eight infant children, left Rousseau with only one child, a daughter named Julia, and immense grief (Shattuck 49). He therefore hoped to take refuge in a new life and pursued painting to offer him comfort and fresh beginnings. Unlike contemporary colleagues of Rousseau who sentimentalize and romanticize the peasant in painting, he is essentially a folk painter and has the hopes and dreams of the average member of his class.
Rousseau’s obsession with being accepted by the art world is somewhat understandable when evaluated in context: as discussed, he was not only uneducated in the ways of formal painting and began his career at a much older age, but he was producing works at the same time as many other talented and better-known modern artists. Though working for many years already, Rousseau did not begin to receive proper recognition for his art until around the same time that Matisse had begun crafting a reputation as an artist. In the book Modern French Painters, author Jan Gordon asserts that the two, while technically competitors in the art arena, were different not only in style and subject matter but also their reasons for painting in the first place: “Matisse was a painter who conceived a terror of painting in a trite way, while Rousseau’s desire was to paint a picture so conventional that he would be admitted to the Artiste Français” (92).

Many a great thinker has postulated an intimate connection between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I believe that at a fundamental level there is a reason for this. As John Keats says in “Ode on a Grecian Urn”, “Beauty is truth, truth beauty- That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know.” Much of what we know in life is learned via education or experience. However, we seem to appreciate ethics and aesthetics, as Keats implies, without being taught in these expected ways. Both ethics and aesthetics are an attempt to describe rather then prescribe. Our studies of morality and beauty are, for the most part, attempts to explain why a piece of art or literature is beautiful, or why an action is moral, rather than a set of rules for judging, or creating, good art or moral behavior. 
	More to the point, criticism of art or morals is never able to fully capture the essence of what is good or what is beautiful. A conversation about the worth of da Vinci's Mona Lisa, for example, may center around concepts like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but in the end, these do not describe why it is good art. Rather, when one is asked about a favorite work of art or literature it is common to hear a phrase similar to, “There's just something about it” preceding a more complex or critical explanation. I believe that both art and morals can never be completely reduced to a description of their qualities. As Flannery O'Connor says, “A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way . . . you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate.” No matter how completely we describe the properties of a work of literature, there is something transcendent which is still left. I believe that ethics has this same property. As Wittgenstein says, “It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental. / . I suggest that it is this “something”, this je ne sais quoi, which is art and morality's most powerful attribute, and that this transcendental nature of both ethics and aesthetics provides a connection point between them.
	I believe that morality and art are so closely related because we experience both of them most powerfully at a noumenally, to use a Kantian term. They impact us at a level that can be experienced, but not fully explained. This link is even stronger when it comes to the art of literature. As McKean says, “What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, music, for instance, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values. . . . Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there” .

The Germany of today is considered a strong force, a united country with its own blend of culture from within the shadows of the alps in München, all the way to Baltic sea city of Kiel.  The same culture can be felt from Köln on the river Rhine, through the centre of Germany to the Saxon city of Dresden located on the Elbe. With such a unique culture, it shouldn't be surprising that Germany as we now know it comes from several different sources, and tribes. 

Germania is the ancestral land of the Germans. The origins of the name are highly disputed among scholars and historians. Tacitus claimed that the name came from a Germanic Tribe known then as Tungrians, and that they had previously been known as Germans before they crossed the Rhine and battled the Gaulish forces (Tacitus, 98.) Julius Caesar first used the word “Germanus” in his commentary on the Gallic Wars where he put down the Gauls and battled with Germanic tribes which crossed the Rhine often under mischievous premisses. He took this word from The Gauls themselves, and used it to distinguish between those which he had conquered (The Gauls) and those which he had not. While the origin is uncertain, some believe it referred to a neighbor in the Gaulish language. In the first chapter, of his first book on these wars, Julius Caesar notes: “Germans, who dwell beyond the Rhine, with whom they (The Gauls) are continually waging war.....They contend with the Germans in almost daily battles.” (Julius Caesar, 50-40 BC) Others claim the meaning comes from the spear that they used in warfare, known as a ger (O.E.D, 2010), or perhaps from the Old Irish word garim meaning “to shout”, which indicated the Germans were loud, or noisy. (Names of Germany) 

 The early Roman historian Tacitus recorded in his AD 98 writing “De Origine et situ Germanorum”, which told of the origins of the Germans, that “I should regard (The Germans) as aboriginal, and not mixed at all with other races through immigration or intercourse. For, in former times it was not by land but on shipboard that those who sought to emigrate would arrive.......Who would leave Asia, or Africa, for Italy for Germany, with its wild country, its inclement skies, its sullen manners and aspect, unless indeed it were his home?(SIC)” (Tacitus, 98) 

And who would leave Rome for Germania? Certainly not the Romans, not yet at least. They would send out their conquests into the lands of Germania for goods, and lead the occasional land campaign but in the end they mostly returned back home to their sprawling empire. So as the Germanic tribes began appearing in the middle of the first century, they lived on the borders of the Roman Empire and traded their goods taken from the land, and their skills by serving within the ranks of the Roman army, (Ozment, 2005 pg. 17.)

The play Twelfth Night seems to say that although disguise is in fact useful in perpetrating long bouts of deception, in the end a person must reject that newly formed guise, or else risk losing themselves forever in the process. A big problem with ending a deception, however, is that one may find themselves alienated in the process. Therefore, in the end, one must decide between one’s own self preservation, or the preservation of relationships with those around them. For although some will respond neutrally to discovering that they’ve been tricked, still others will not take the deception so lightly, and will be likely be offended by the whole charade.
The topic of deception in gender role reversal is especially problematic, because it brings up many side issues, perhaps the most important one being, why? Why does the subject feel the need to shirk their own identity and take up a disguise in the form of the opposite gender? In Viola’s case, it is obviously a form of self protection.: “I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249)
Having newly arrived in a foreign land, Viola feels it necessary to pretend to be a man to protect herself from would be attackers. Viola’s plan works, but it also alienates her from the women around her, cutting her off from an important support system. To make matters worse, she is apparently so convincing at appearing to be a man that Olivia confuses her with Sebastian, and in effect falls in love with her. “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138) On top of that, she also has to deal with suppressed romantic desires between her and Orsino: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1. 260-261)
Although this may be a somewhat progressive attitude, to the modern reader, Twelfth Night may be seen as an illustration of how deception may help facilitate the unveiling of suppressed emotions, especially in the cases of Olivia and Orsino. Certain passages seem to hint that the aforesaid characters may have unexpressed subconscious desires that the appearance of Viola/Cesario forces them to deal with. For instance, is Olivia attracted to Cesario because Cesario appears to be a man, or does Olivia really secretly harbor feelings for women? One would argue that this is probably not the case, because Shakespeare’s character Olivia seems more likely to be parodying those people of his time period who judge others only upon their looks. 
This is evidenced by the ease with which Olivia switches her romantic ardors from Cesario to Sebastian, and begins to regard Cesario/Viola as family rather than a love interest: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315)

German colonial rule has been noted by various observers for its brutality, notably with respect to the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. Of course nothing so broad as an entire colonial empire can be accounted for by such a simple description. The German colonial empire was as varied in policies and ruling style as it was in geography. Educational provision across the colonies was similarly diverse. When the British took over German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they found a large population of educated and literate Africans. German educational efforts in Kamerun and other colonies were also praised by contemporary authors. 
The situation in South West Africa (present-day Namibia) presented a stark contrast.  Unlike in East Africa, where the government established state schools and played a prominent role in the education of the natives, in South West Africa the task of native education was left almost entirely to missionary societies that received limited government support. The government did however invest significant resources towards the education of Europeans in the colony, establishing s system of state schools as well as more heavily supporting and regulating missionary schools. These educational policies had longstanding effects on South West Africa, even after German rule. While other German colonies boasted significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa “the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate.” Various social, political, and economic factors led to the divergent experience of South West Africa. This paper seeks to expand the discussion by identifying these factors and paying particular attention to new research on the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities to native Africans.
There is a wealth of literature dealing with education in the German colonial empire specifically. Most of these sources are in German and were written in the early twentieth century, during or shortly after the period of German colonial rule. The aim of early works was primarily to describe the features of educational systems in these colonies. Later writings in English expanded the discourse through comparative studies of education in the various German colonies and more detailed analyses of specific aspects of education. These studies illustrated significant differences in the educational systems of different colonies. The most prominent work to explicitly address the topic of this paper is Cohen’s study of education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen compares the educational systems of the two colonies and discusses the factors that account for the differences between them. According to Cohen, the large settler population of South West Africa explains many of the distinguishing aspects of the colony’s educational system.
Compared to Germany’s other colonial possessions, South West Africa had a moderately temperate climate, although much of the territory is covered by arid desert. The European population of South West Africa reflected the relatively hospitable conditions. By 1913 nearly 15,000 whites lived in South West Africa, while only 5,336 lived in the colony with the next largest settler population, East Africa.

The United States of America and Mexico are an example of two nations which at one time were beset by an enduring rivalry which spanned 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. (Diehl and Goerts 2000 p. 145).  The high-water mark of this rivalry was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, where the United States attacked and defeated Mexico and secured for itself Texas and the American Southwest as new territory.  Many other clashes happened between the two nations, finally abating just before the First World War.   The rivalry began as Americans and Mexicans clashed on key issues such as religion, culture and tradition and had a major clash of material interests (Schmitt 1974 p. 30-31).   
	This is not unlike many other nations who have an enduring rivalry with a neighbor.  Nations which share a border tend to have clashes of interests which lend to the creation of rival positions between the nations.  The United States and Mexico are not unlike many other enduring rivalries between nations which share a common border.  David M. Pletcher (1977) states that “Only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting overarching American diplomatic problems” (p. 41).  Indeed, both of these nations are geographically close to the United States and have been rivals to the United States, while other nations in Latin America enjoy and have enjoyed good relations with the United States.   
	Religious issues created a rift between the two nations, a problem which has beset many nations through history.  Sally Frahm (2001) states that ”if in the twentieth century Americans were opposed to fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth they were opposed to Catholicism and monarchy”  (p.86).  Not unlike the Cold War’s rivalry between the United States and the Soviet Union was part ideological struggle and part a competition over interests each nation deemed vital. In this case, however, the ideological struggles weren’t based on the political structure but on instead the religious preferences of the United States and Mexico.  This distrust grew from the distrust between the English and Spanish.  Inheriting these feelings of distrust from their former colonial rulers was a major obstacle in the establishment of amiable foreign relations between the United States and Mexico.
	Diehl and Goerts (2000) list 17 disputes between Mexico and the United States in the 57-year rivalry period.   The majority of disputes between the rivalry period described by Diehl and Goerts are territorial issues relating to border raids from Mexican territory into Mexico and other frontier problems.  Border raids by bandits and outlaws from on American border towns were a major problem which remained until both the United States and Mexico exerted military force on their borders (Schmitt 1974 p. 97).  
Schmitt (1974) explains the rivalry between the two nation began to abate as “Mexico became clearly dependent on the United States in a substantial way” (p. 109) and finally ended as American ambitions “changed from territorial expansion to economic intervention into Mexico” (p.110) in the later part of the 19th Century.

Fifteen‭ ‬years ago I became suddenly and unexpectedly disabled by an illness I never knew existed. 

 I was a nurse at the time. I had chosen my profession out of a deeply entrenched need for the safety and security I didn't have as a child. ‭"‬You'll always be able to find work‭; ‬people will always get sick.‭" ‬was the mantra I heard over and over as I reached adolescence and beyond. So--‭ ‬even though my dream was to be a scientist or a journalist-preferably a little of both,‭ ‬I chose nursing. 

Nevertheless,‭ ‬there I was:‭ ‬46‭ ‬years old and single,‭ ‬no money in the bank to speak of and unable to work. To this day I am disabled,‭ ‬and after‭ ‬15‭ ‬years of living on Social Security Disability,‭ ‬I have literally nothing left that I can call‭ "‬mine.‭" ‬I get by,‭ ‬but every day is a struggle and an assault on my security,‭ ‬safety and self-esteem. Nothing in my life is certain anymore,‭ ‬yet,‭ ‬there is one thing that I know to be true. I could not have gotten by for all these years were it not for the help of my family and a few good friends,‭ ‬no matter how strong I was. And believe me,‭ ‬when real disaster strikes,‭ ‬you do not feel very strong at all. 

My point is that there will always be emergencies in life-big and small.  There are no guarantees and no matter how well one prepares,‭ ‬some things are just too big to overcome on your own. 

I agree wholeheartedly that we in the U.S. need to stop putting all of our eggs in big government's‭ "‬basket‭"; ‬Lord knows it is moldy‭ ‬and falling apart,‭ ‬anyway. Yet I would much rather see Americans learning to trust one another again‭–‬learning to help each other and to ask for help,‭ ‬rather‭ ‬than have each of us individually clambering out to the backyard to build fallout shelters. 

The Conservatives in the US talk about the‭ "‬rugged individualism‭" ‬that built this country‭; ‬but in truth,‭ ‬what kept our forefathers going in hard times wasn't rugged individualism,‭ ‬it was compassion,‭ ‬mutual respect and the sharing of resources. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies in wagon trains didn't make it to the coast by going it alone. 


So,‭ ‬by all means,‭ ‬be prepared. I am. I have a disaster kit‭; ‬first‭ ‬aid supplies,‭ ‬water purifying tablets and plastic sheeting and duct tape for the windows in the event of a biological attack. I have several flashlights and all sorts of batteries,‭ ‬lots and lots of candles and waterproof matches and canned goods,‭ ‬too. If‭ ‬you have the land and the resources for a small farm and the ability to can or preserve your own food-do it. It's a great idea,‭ ‬as is a wood stove,‭ ‬as long as you do not live in an apartment. 

But while you are at it,‭ ‬get to know your neighbors.

Sometime in the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince who would one day be called Buddha was born. Over the course of his life, he renounced the world and became enlightened, and his teachings led to the formation of Buddhism—the most orthodox sect of which is known as Theravada Buddhism. The religion is around twenty five hundred years old; it looks different today than it did when Buddha was alive. This can be seen all over, for instance in the Theravada nation of Sri Lanka, where the annual water-cutting ceremony is observed. Monks and laymen alike participate in this ceremony, and it holds some religious significance, despite Buddha never teaching about any festivity of the sort. These differences run all the way from the superficial traditions to the soteriological core of the religion. The Theravada Buddhist community, both from the monastic perspective and from the lay perspective, has had to change its doctrinal principles over time. This can be attributed to forces both external and internal, both hostile and benign.
	There are a number of qualifying terms this discussion will make frequent use of. There is the concept of internal versus external. Here, an internal force is defined as a force borne of members of the Buddhasasana, regardless of monastic status. An external force is any force from non-Buddhists. A hostile force is any force that damages or intends to damage the Buddhist community—a force borne of a negative perception of Buddhism. A benign force is a force that does not wish to harm or help the Buddhist community—though it may end up doing one or the other as a byproduct. These terms will come up repeatedly throughout this discussion.
	First, it is important to investigate the basics of the religion—the doctrines that lie at the core of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists seek refuge in the triple gem of the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is essentially comprised of the Tripitaka—the three baskets—of Buddhist text. The Sutta Pitaka contains all the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka contains the disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka contains the metaphysical components of Buddhism. The metaphysical notions consist of things like Anatta—no soul, Dukkha—inherent suffering in life, and Anicca—impermanence of everything. Only by recognizing these concepts can one end Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth, which happens continuously. Along with Sansara will end lobha—desire, dosa—hatred, and moha—delusion, when one becomes enlightened. In the Vinaya Pitaka, rules for life are set forth. For laymen, there are five precepts (I shall not kill, I shall not lie, I shall not steal, I shall not misbehave sexually, and I shall not take intoxicating substances). For monks, there are many more disciplinary rules to be followed. The most fundamental doctrinal notion in Buddhism is the notion of the four noble truths. First, Dukkha; the truth that life is suffering. Second, that attachment causes suffering. Third, that suffering can be overcome.

Well lemme tell ya, I'm thinkin' about gettin' into this social work thing. I wanna help out kids who've been treated bad or ain't got nothin' goin' for 'em, and try to mend those messed up families.

Now, I ain't just talkin' about doin' the job, I'm talkin' 'bout livin' it.  I believe in treatin' folks right, doin' the honest thing, and always tryin' to make things better, both for folks and for myself.  I wanna learn all I can so I can be the best darn social worker I can be.

 Truth is, I've always felt kinda pulled towards helpin' folks. High school and college, I saw a lot of folks runnin' from their problems, tryin' to deal with 'em in ways that ain't right.  I even got my degree in Psychology, thinkin' that'd lead me somewhere. But I wasn't sure what path to take.  

Then one time, my friend introduced me to this young fella, just sixteen, lookin' all scared and nervous. Turns out, he was runnin' from his folks 'cause they were treatin' him awful. I told the police what I knew, and they asked me to talk to his parents.  Well, let me tell ya, they weren't too happy about it. They tried to make excuses, sayin' he was just bein' manipulative.  That's when I knew, this is what I gotta do. Help these kids, help these families, even when folks don't wanna see it.

And it ain't just about the kids, it's about doin' what's right.  Society talks a big game about lookin' out for each other, but sometimes it feels like we're more worried about fittin' in than standin' up for what's right.  I ain't afraid to be different, to speak my mind, to stand up for those who can't stand up for themselves.  That's what social justice is all about,  and that's what I'm gonna fight for.

Now, lemme tell ya 'bout this here sleep stuff. There's two main ways to look at why folks can't get a good night's rest: the science stuff and the folksy stuff. 

The science folks, they say it's all in your genes, passed down from your momma and daddy. They look at your body, see if there's anything screwy with your insides, makin' it hard to sleep. 

The other folks, they say it's all about where you come from, who you hang with, and what kinda life you lead. They say things like your race, how much money you got, and even what kinda neighborhood you live in can mess with your sleep. 

This here paper, it takes a look at both these ways of thinkin' about sleep problems. It talks 'bout all sorts of studies, seein' if they back up these ideas. And it ain't afraid to call 'em out if they're full of baloney, too!

Now, sleep problems come in all shapes and sizes. Some folks just can't fall asleep, some folks can't stay asleep, and some folks have weird dreams or act all goofy in their sleep.  Some folks get these sleep problems 'cause of other stuff goin' on in their heads, like worry or sadness. 

This paper, though, mostly focuses on sleep problems called insomnia, where folks just can't seem to get a good night's rest. It looks at how both the science folks and the folksy folks explain this problem.

One study, for example, looked at mice and their little sleep brains. They found that some tiny parts in the mice's brains that control sleepin' and wakin' had something called GABAB receptors.  Turns out, if these receptors are messed up, it can make the mice sleepy all the time! The scientists think this might be true for humans, too.  So, maybe some folks have sleepy genes!  

This study shows us that sleep problems can be caused by both our genes and our environment. What we eat, how much we exercise, and even the stress we feel can all affect how well we sleep.

Alright, so listen up!  This here's about this thing called CAPD, which is like when your brain has trouble makin' sense of what you hear.  It ain't that you can't hear nothin', it's just that your brain's gettin' all mixed up tryin' to figure out what folks are sayin'. Kinda like tryin' to understand someone talkin' real fast, or when there's a bunch of noise goin' on around 'em.

Now, how do ya know if someone's got this CAPD thing? Well, there's a few telltale signs, kinda like red flags.  They might have trouble followin' conversations, especially if there's a lot goin' on. Or maybe they struggle to tell where a sound is comin' from. Sometimes they can't tell the difference between two sounds that are real close together, like tryin' to pick out one voice in a crowd.

So, what can ya do if you're a teacher and one of your students has CAPD?  Well, ya gotta be patient, see? And maybe try speakin' a little slower and clearer.  And make sure they're sittin' in a spot where they can hear ya good, away from all the distractions.  Maybe even use some visual aids, like pictures or gestures, to help 'em understand.

Now listen, this play, Twelfth Night, it's kinda sayin' that while wearin' a mask, pretendin' to be someone you ain't, can work for a while,  it can mess you up real bad if ya keep it up. You start to lose yourself in all that pretendin', and that ain't good.  The problem is, when you gotta drop the act, folks might get mad. You might even lose the friendships you made while wearin' the mask. It's like, do you stay true to yourself, or keep up the charade to keep everyone happy?  Some folks might not care if you've been pullin' the wool over their eyes, but others, well, they might take it real hard.

This whole pretendin' thing gets really tricky when it comes to gender, see? It makes ya wonder, why'd you start wearin' the mask in the first place? Like, what's drivin' ya to be someone you ain't? In this play, Viola, she's gotta pretend to be a man to stay safe. She's in a new place, all alone, and it's a rough world out there for a woman. So she puts on the disguise, and it works, but it also cuts her off from the other women. She's all alone, even though she's surrounded by folks.  

Then there's this whole mess with Olivia, who falls head over heels for "Cesario", thinking he's a man.  And to top it off, Viola's got feelings for Orsino, but she can't act on 'em because she's playin' the part of a man.  It's a whole tangled web, ain't it?

Maybe the whole thing is supposed to show us that pretendin' can bring out feelings we don't even know we got, like with Olivia and Orsino. Maybe they're  strugglin' with stuff they ain't even aware of, and Viola just makes 'em face it head-on.  Or maybe Olivia's just a bit shallow, fallin' for whoever looks good, regardless of who they really are. She kinda ditches Cesario the second Sebastian shows up, and then suddenly Cesario's just family.  Kind of makes ya think about who we really love and why.

Well, lemme tell ya, them Germans, they weren't all sunshine and rainbows when it came to runnin' their colonies. They got a real nasty reputation, especially for what they did to the Ovaherero and Nama folks in South West Africa, back when it was called that. But you can't just paint the whole darn empire with one brush, you know? Just like a pack of hounds, they acted different in different parts of the world. Same goes for their schools. Sometimes they built their own schools and taught the natives, other times they just let the fellas in funny hats do it.

Now, in East Africa, where the Brits took over later, they found a bunch of folks who could read and write. The Germans had done some good there, some folks even said so back then. But down in South West Africa, it was a whole different story. They didn't care much for teachin' the locals. They mostly left that to the missionaries, who weren't exactly rolling in dough. 

They were real keen on teachin' the white folks though, buildin' fancy schools and makin' sure the missionaries were doin' it right.  This messed things up real bad for South West Africa, even after the Germans were gone.  While other places had lots of smart folks, South West Africa was stuck in the dark ages. Nobody knew nothin' but their own language and traditions. 

Why was it so different? That's what this paper's gonna try to figure out. We're gonna look at the folks who lived there, the folks who ran the show, and see what made them tick.  There's been a lotta books written about this, mostly in German, back when the Germans were still runnin' things. They mostly just described how the schools worked. But later, some folks wrote in English, comparing all the different parts of the German empire and lookin' closer at what made each place tick.

Ya know, music these days, it's gotten crazy! There's so many different kinds of it, like rock, country, jazz, rap, even folk. And each one of them has got its own little offshoots, like branches on a tree. But heavy metal, that's something else. It's like the whole forest exploded, with all these different kinds of trees growing everywhere.

It all started about forty years ago, and people started realizing they could make this music really loud and intense, kinda like a dark storm cloud. They weren't afraid to sing about the tough stuff, the things that make you think, the bad times, ya know? And the music, man, it's got this power to it, all those guitars and drums, it just grabs you.

Now, there are so many different kinds of heavy metal, it's hard to say what it really is anymore. It's like a melting pot, with bits and pieces of all these other genres mixed in. But you gotta remember, it all started somewhere.

Heavy metal is more than just music, it's a whole attitude. It's about pushing the limits, being loud and proud, and not being afraid to be different. It's about the darkness, the raw emotion, the things that most people try to hide. Back in the seventies, there were all these drugs around, and they made people wanna express themselves in new and crazy ways. That's where a lot of the heavy metal sound came from. 

And you know what?  It's still going strong today. People still love that dark energy, that feeling of being alive.

Well, lemme tell ya, this here Henri Rousseau fella, he was a dreamer, just like those fancy Surrealists, but he was doin' it way back before they came along. See, he painted this picture called "The Dream" back in 1910. Now, it ain't just some lady lookin' at pretty stuff in her dream, it's Rousseau himself dreamin' big dreams about bein' a famous painter. He wanted folks to like his work, ya know, to be recognized and all that jazz. But here's the thing, he was stuck in this pickle. He wanted to be accepted by the art snobs, but he also wanted to paint his own way, not just copy what everyone else was doin'.  It was a real head-scratcher for him.

Now, lemme tell ya a little about this Rousseau guy. He wasn't born with a silver spoon in his mouth, not like those fancy art kids. He was a simple man, worked for the government collectin' tolls, nothin' fancy. He lost his wife and kids, so he turned to paintin' to make himself feel better. But he really wanted to be taken seriously as an artist.

Problem was, he was up against some real tough competition. These other artists, they were already famous and makin' a name for themselves.  He was like a late bloomer, tryin' to catch up.  Some folks say he just wanted to paint somethin' so plain and simple that those fancy art folks would finally say, "Hey, that ain't bad!" But wouldn't ya know it, that's what made him different.

Lotsa smart folks have said that good stuff and pretty stuff go together, same as truth and beauty. I reckon there's a reason for that. Like that fella Keats, he said, "Beauty is truth, truth beauty— That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know." We learn a lot in life from books and doin' things, but we just seem to know when somethin' is right or pretty, without havin' to be taught. Both good stuff and pretty stuff are about describin' things, not tellin' ya how to do it. When we talk about what makes somethin' good art or right, we're mostly just tryin' to figure out why it is that way, not makin' rules for makin' it.

Here's the thing, though: ya can't ever really put yer finger on what makes somethin' good or pretty.  Talkin' 'bout da Vinci's Mona Lisa, ya might say things like the way the front and back are done, or the colors, or even what kinda time it was made in. But that don't really tell ya why it's so darn good. When folks talk 'bout their favorite art or story, they'll often say somethin' like, "There's just somethin' about it," before they can even begin to explain it. 

I reckon art and good stuff can't be fully explained, just like Flannery O'Connor said, "A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way . . . you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate.” No matter how much ya describe somethin', there's always somethin' more, somethin' special that ya just can't put into words. I think that's what makes art and good stuff so powerful.  It's that somethin' special, that je ne sais quoi, that connects 'em.

I think art and good stuff are so close because we feel 'em deep down, in a way that's hard to explain.  Like when ya read a good book, it gets ya right in the gut. Literature especially, because it's all about values, just like life.  We love literature because it shows us what matters.

Germany today is a real powerhouse, a united country with its own unique culture. You can feel it everywhere, from the fancy city of München in the mountains to the coastal town of Kiel by the Baltic Sea. It's the same in Köln on the Rhine River, all the way through to Dresden, a cool old city on the Elbe River. With a culture this unique, it shouldn't surprise anyone that modern Germany is made up of lots of different groups and tribes.

Now, Germania is where the Germans came from way back in the day.  Folks can't agree on how the name came about, even the smart historians!  One guy named Tacitus said it came from a German tribe called the Tungrians, who were called Germans before they crossed the Rhine and fought with the Gauls (Tacitus, 98).  Julius Caesar, famous for his wars with the Gauls, was the first to use the word "Germanus" in his writings. He used it to separate the Gauls he conquered from the Germans who kept crossing the Rhine and causing trouble (Caesar, 50-40 BC). Some think Caesar got the word from the Gauls themselves, who used it to talk about their neighbors.  In his first book about the Gallic Wars, Caesar says, "Germans, who dwell beyond the Rhine, with whom they (The Gauls) are continually waging war.....They contend with the Germans in almost daily battles.” (Caesar, 50-40 BC) Others say "German" comes from their fighting spears, called "ger" (O.E.D, 2010), or maybe from an old Irish word meaning "to shout," which means the Germans were loud and noisy (Names of Germany).

A Roman writer named Tacitus, back in 98 AD, wrote a book called "De Origine et situ Germanorum" about where the Germans came from. He thought they were completely original, not mixed with other people from other places. He said, “I should regard (The Germans) as aboriginal, and not mixed at all with other races through immigration or intercourse. For, in former times it was not by land but on shipboard that those who sought to emigrate would arrive.......Who would leave Asia, or Africa, for Italy for Germany, with its wild country, its inclement skies, its sullen manners and aspect, unless indeed it were his home?” (Tacitus, 98)

And who'd want to leave Rome for Germania?  Not the Romans, not at first anyway! They went into Germania to get things they wanted and fought battles sometimes, but mostly they went home to their big empire. So, while the Germanic tribes were around in the first century, they lived on the edge of the Roman Empire. They traded the stuff they got from the land and even fought in the Roman army (Ozment, 2005 pg. 17).

I looked down, my mind kinda blank, just taking in what was in front of me.  I wasn't feelin' nothin' much, just kinda watchin' it all go down. My brain was workin', but it wasn't makin' no real sense of it, just like, seein' stuff and lettin' it go.  Thoughts were poppin' in and out like fireflies, real quick and easy. It was like my mind was a river, just flowin' on by.  

Remember that art book I got, "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain"?  Ever since I was a kid, I wanted to learn how to draw, and this book was supposed to teach ya everything, right down to how your brain sees lines. One trick they show you is to put a square around somethin' you wanna draw, like a bowl of fruit on a table, and that turns it into just the bowl of fruit, simple like that.

But lookin' at this thing, I couldn't do that. It was too much, you know? Picasso had his blue period, Monet loved all them greens, and the old Italian guys, they used every color under the sun.  If I was gonna call myself an artist, then this was my start, my story, my "Work in Brown".  

So, I grabbed my tool, my hand moved, my mind tryin' to make somethin' outta nothin'. The water was calm, clean, and clear.  Stuff was breakin' off and floatin' away.  Then my hand got all tight, like I was nervous, and I slammed the handle of the toilet.  That brown thing wouldn't budge, stuck like glue.

Mop in my hand, standin' there with my tie chokin' me, I just stared at this thing someone left behind.  A few more flushes, a few more moments of thinkin' about nothin', then I grabbed the toilet paper and wrapped myself up like a glove.  Standin' up, then bendin' over, I reached into the bowl, like a mama checkin' on her turkey in the oven...

Teenagers, dang, they're killin' themselves out there on the road! It's a real mess, y'all.  The brainiacs at the National Institutes of Health say our young'uns ain't quite got the noggin' for drivin' yet.  It's like givin' a 2x4 to a chihuahua - ain't gonna end well! They're just inexperienced, plain and simple. That means more wrecks, more roll-overs, more speedin', more cars endin' up in ditches than ya can shake a stick at.  

And don't even get me started on havin' their buddies in the car!  Somebody smarter than me down in California did a study and figured out that the more little buckaroos in the car, the more likely somethin's gonna go sideways. 

Now, they're tryin' to fix it with these fancy "provisional" licenses, limitin' the hours they can drive and who they can haul around.  But that ain't gonna cut it!  The problem is, they're just not ready.  

This fella Zuckerman, a real smart cookie, says even 18 is too young! Says kids under 20 just gotta have that need for speed, like they're lookin' for trouble. 

So, we gotta wait 'til they grow up a bit, ya know?  My momma always said, "Patience is a virtue," and she was right!  Otherwise, we're gonna have more wrecks than a demolition derby, especially with all those baby boomers' kids gettin' their licenses soon. 

We gotta do somethin', y'all.  Schools can teach 'em about drivin', but nobody under 18 should be behind the wheel.  Maybe a permit first, then some extra practice time with a responsible adult.  Just like the other states, we gotta make it a national thing, ya know?  Keepin' those young'uns safe is what matters most!

So I was looking through these old movies from way back when Edison was makin' 'em.  Found fifteen of these "trick" movies from 1895 to 1901. These things are all about makin' stuff look like magic, ya know? I basically tried to figure out how they made 'em work and see if any of the later ones were doin' somethin' different. Most of these old movies, they're stuck in one spot, just like a stage play. No fancy mov'in' around the camera, just straight-on shots, nothin' fancy like you see now.  But some of 'em, they started to break the rules a little bit, doin' things like havin' more than one shot, which was pretty daring back then.

One thing all these trick movies got in common is they're filmed like a stage play. Picture a curtain, that's what these movies are like. The camera sits right there, like it's in the front row of the audience, and it don't move.  That's how they did it back then, just like those vaudeville shows, you know? The actors can only walk back and forth, never comin' right at ya or walkin' away. Like in this one movie, "Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel," the fellas come in from one side and just move back and forth. The camera don't follow 'em anywhere.

Because they're stuck in this one spot, the shots are all long and sometimes medium.  They never get up close to anyone's face, not even once.  That's how they did it in those old theaters, too, you had to see the whole scene at once.

And most of these trick movies, they're just one big shot, start to finish. Like one idea, one whole movie. That's why they're so short, maybe a minute or less. They're more like those little tricks you see in vaudeville, magic and stuff.

But here's the thing, what they call one shot ain't always one real shot. Sometimes they put a bunch of 'em together to make it look like somethin' is disappearin' or comin' back.  Take "The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots," that one's from way back.  If you look real close, you can see where they cut together a bunch of shots to make it look like her head is comin' off.

Listen up, folks! This John Taylor fella, he was a real firebrand back in the day, a true-blue Republican. Now, he was a farmer, through and through, but that didn't stop him from talkin' his mind on politics. He was all about freedom, you know, for himself and everyone else. And let me tell ya, he believed that a farmer's way of life was the best way to live. That's what shaped his whole outlook on government, from how it should be run to what it should be allowed to do.

He thought America had a real chance to get things right, see? No old traditions to hold us back, so we could build our own government, one where folks could rule themselves. He was a big believer in folks' natural rights, that everyone's equally important and deserve to be treated right. He thought those rights should be protected from the government, because if one guy gets trampled, it messes up everything for everyone.

Taylor, he was a firm believer in good and evil, black and white. He said, "Government's run by people, so it's gonna have all the good and bad that comes with people."  He wanted a government that protected your stuff, helped farmers out, and kept big businesses in check. He figured a good government, even if run by selfish folks, would still do right by everyone. He just wanted those in charge to remember that their job was to help the common man, not line their own pockets.

Now, Taylor, he was a stickler for the Constitution. He wanted the government to stick to what it said in there, plain and simple. He knew a big government would be expensive and likely get out of control. But he also knew just reading the words wasn't enough. You gotta understand what the guys who wrote it meant! And he thought the Declaration of Independence was even more important, because it showed that America was made up of separate states, not just one big country.

Listen up, 'cause I gotta tell ya 'bout this project we had. Figure 17 shows us folks weren't fillin' out them commuter logs like they used to. Kinda bummed me out, to be honest, 'cause I couldn't figure out why.  See, it was winter in New England, ya know, and folks ain't ridin' bikes or walkin' much when it's freezin' their butts off. December also means everyone's swamped with schoolwork and grades, so forgettin' about a log ain't exactly unheard of. Plus, December's when the holidays hit, and everyone's off vacationin' or visitin' family, so why'd they need to come to campus anyway?  Classes start back up in January, but that doesn't explain why folks weren't fillin' out them logs in February either. Maybe folks just got excited at the start, and then the spark died down.  

We tried to shake things up with the "Carpool Challenge Week" in March, kinda like a pep rally for carpoolin'.  Got folks submittin' logs again, but it was a real struggle to keep 'em goin'.  See, college life is all about breaks and holidays, and it's tough to get folks pumped about carpoolin' when they're busy havin' fun or just needin' a break.

Another thing is, folks love their cars. It's just how we are, ya know? So, to get 'em carpoolin', we had to bribe 'em with goodies. Gift cards to restaurants, coffee shops, and even a massage!  We even had some bigger stores throwin' in some goodies.  Think about it, though:  what if we had a shiny new bike, a fancy hybrid car, or even an electric car up for grabs? Maybe that'd get folks more excited.  We kinda stuck with the same ol' prizes, though.  If we'd upped the ante, maybe folks would have kept carpoolin' longer.

Well lemme tell ya 'bout these fancy ETF things. They're like a basket of investments, kinda like them index funds, but you can buy 'em and sell 'em like regular stocks. You get the spread out risk of a whole bunch of stuff, but you can also do some fancy tricks like borrowing money to buy more or even betting against 'em. And the best part? They cost less to run than them mutual funds.

Now, there's a catch, ya gotta pay a fee every time you buy or sell one, just like a stock.  And even though they sound great, you gotta make sure you're really getting that spread out risk they promise.  So I was lookin' at this ETF called IHF, and I figured I'd see if it was really worth it compared to just buyin' the biggest ten stocks inside it. 

It turns out, IHF has ten biggies that make up most of what's inside. I figured, why not just buy those ten straight up?  So I did the math, and guess what? Buying just those ten stocks actually gives ya a better return and less risk than buyin' the whole IHF thing!

Now, I ain't sayin' that's always gonna be the case, but it sure looks like it in this situation. It's like gettin' a bigger bang for your buck by just pickin' the best ten.

This Edgar Allan Poe poem, "Dream-Land," is one of his favorites. Poe uses the word "Thulé" a couple of times, and folks like Mabbott say he got it from Virgil. Virgil used it to talk about an island way up north, beyond Britain, that folks back then thought was the edge of the known world. Now, Virgil probably did use the word, but there's another writer Poe liked a lot, a German fella named Goethe, and some folks think Poe might have gotten the word from him too.

This is important because it shows Poe knew all about Goethe's writing. This guy, Karl J. Arndt, wrote a book comparing Poe's "Politian" to Goethe's "Mignon" and thinks Poe was really copying Goethe.

You see, Oxford says Goethe was a big deal, famous for writing a play called "Faust." It's a long one, in two parts, with the first part coming out in 1808 and the second one right when Goethe died, in 1832.  Inside the second part of "Faust" is a little poem called "The King of Thulé." It's about this king whose wife dies after giving him a special cup. He starts drinking a lot and crying over her. Eventually, he decides he wants to die too, gives his stuff to his kids, keeps the cup, walks to a cliff, throws the cup in the ocean, closes his eyes, and kicks the bucket.  The King of Thulé and the guy in Poe's poem are kinda similar, maybe like a dark twin of Poe's own sadness and how he used to drink too much.  "Faust" was also turned into a play by this guy, H P Grattan, in 1842, just a year before Poe used "Thulé" in "The Pit and the Pendulum."

Poe uses "Thulé" twice in his writing. He uses "ultma Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum," but in "Dream-Land," he uses "Thulé" at the beginning and end of the poem, like bookends. You can almost think of "The King of Thulé" and "Dream-Land" as going together. In "Dream-Land," the speaker talks about this dark, lonely place called Thulé, where he's haunted by dead friends and everything is gray and lifeless.  You can see the same feelings in "The King of Thulé," where Goethe's king is also lonely, lost, and doesn't want to live anymore. It's like Poe stepped right into Goethe's poem.

Goethe was a big deal, and Poe would have known about him, especially since Poe loved Tennyson. When someone asked Poe if he admired Tennyson, he said, "Yes, and Goethe!" Aside from that connection to Tennyson, Poe would have read a lot of Goethe's stuff because it was being reprinted a lot after it first came out.

So, this lady, Jennifer Palmer, took a spill in a grocery store 'cause some applesauce was left sittin' on the floor.  Now, she's sayin' the store manager, this Martin fella, knew about the spill,  heard about it twice, but didn't do nothin' about it for half an hour 'cause he was eatin' dinner.  She wants to sue him for damages, not just for her hurt, but 'cause she says he acted real mean and reckless.

Now, the judge ain't gonna toss her case out right away. To get those extra damages, she's gotta prove Martin knew he was doin' somethin' dangerous, that he was basically messin' with folks' safety on purpose. She's gonna say, see, other folks had slipped and fallen there before, so Martin shoulda known better.  

Whether he acted real bad, that's a bit harder to say. The judge might think it was just plain dumb, not necessarily mean, but it ain't lookin' good for Martin. 

Here's the deal: 

This Rich Wayne, he works at the store, tells Martin about the applesauce spill around 5:00. Martin says he's on a break and doesn't wanna deal with it. Then, Mary Haddigan, another worker, tells Martin about the spill again at 5:15, same story from Martin.

Finally, at 5:30, Palmer comes along, slips on that applesauce, and bam! Bad back.

It turns out, this ain't the first time folks have fallen in this store. Five times already that year, folks had gone down.  Palmer's sayin' Martin knew or shoulda known things were dangerous and didn't do nothin'.

Well, lemme tell ya somethin'.  A few years back, I took this class on Islam, and we got into a real hollerin' match about whether it was a religion that wanted to bash yer head in or not.  Now, more than ever, that question's got me scratchin' my head.  Look at how things've changed since 9/11.  The media, they went from slammin' Islam and them extremists to coddlin' it like a baby.  I'll bet you a dang dollar we couldn't have had a fella like Barack Obama runnin' for president back then, what with his Muslim roots and all. 

Now, I gotta say, this story 'bout Muhammad, the prophet fella, it got me thinkin'.  See, I figured Muhammad was a real tough hombre, the kinda guy who'd take over tribes and force 'em to turn Muslim.  But this here biography, it paints him as some kind of martyr, misunderstood and humble.  Like folks just kinda wandered in, saw the light, and joined up.  Seems fishy to me, like they're tryin' to make him out to be somethin' he ain't.

And get this, there's some real spooky similarities between Muhammad and Jesus.  Like when he turned some mutton and milk into enough for forty guys.  It's like they're tryin' to steal Jesus' thunder, makin' Muhammad look all holy and miraculous too.  Ain't that a kick in the pants?

Then there's all these stories about folks convertin' on their own, but they're all secondhand accounts, hear-say, somethin' like "So-and-so told me that So-and-so said..."  Gives me the creeps, makes it all sound like a bunch of baloney.

But the thing that really gets my goat is how they try to make Muhammad out to be this sweet talkin', wise guy.  But history says somethin' different, and I just can't help but wonder if Muslims today know the real deal about how Muhammad came to power.

Well, let me tell you somethin'.  After Jesus kicked the bucket, folks started preachin' about him in ways he probably wouldn't have liked.  Seems like Christianity got further and further from its roots over the years.  Nowadays, folks are gettin' more open-minded and wantin' things to change.  Some old-timers, though, they cling to the old ways and don't want nothin' new.  But they ain't gonna be the ones callin' the shots.  In time, more and more Christians are gonna want to go back to the basics, the stuff Jesus actually taught.  It might take a while, maybe even a hundred years or more, but it's gonna happen.  

Think of it like rewindin' a tape.  We're gonna strip away all the extra stuff that got added over the years and get back to what Jesus was all about.  It's gonna start slow, but then it'll pick up steam.  Folks are gonna start thinkin' more like they did back when Jesus was around.  And guess what?  The churches, they'll be right there leadin' the way!  But instead of everyone bein' different, we'll all start thinkin' alike.  Like when different teams all join together to win a game.  

History's full of these big turnarounds.  Remember when Christians were bein' persecuted by the Romans?  Well, look what happened!  The Romans became Christians themselves!  And in our own country, we went from slaves to leaders.   

This time, it's gonna be the same thing, only with religion.  We're gonna go back to the start, back to Jesus, and everybody's gonna be on the same page.   One thing that'll help this happen is folks startin' to see Jesus' words as somethin' more like a story, not just plain facts.   

So, what happened after Jesus?  Well, if you go way back, you see that it all started with Judaism.   They believed in one God, and they had these special books called the scriptures that they thought came from God.   The Jewish people weren't all on the same page, though.  There were different groups, like the Sadducees, the Pharisees, and the Essenes.  But they all shared some basic beliefs.

You see, this book, "The Jungle," it shows us that folks deep down, they're just out for themselves. They wanna make their lives as good as they can be, but they don't give a hoot about anyone less fortunate. It's all about lookin' out number one. Take those factory bosses, for example. They just wanna make their factories bigger and richer,  not a darn bit of care about who gets hurt in the process.  The book says it plain as day, these factories are like monsters, belchin' out smoke like it's nobody's business. They don't care about the people or the animals, just their bottom line. They're like those guys who drive their big trucks and don't even look when they pull out, runnin' over anything in their way. 

And those factory bosses, they don't care about their workers neither. They're just lookin' to squeeze every last penny they can out of 'em. They work 'em 'til they drop, then fire 'em without a second thought.  The whole place is just a mess of jealousy and hatred, everyone's lookin' out for themselves, 'cause nobody's lookin' out for 'em. These workers, they're like slaves, trapped in this system where they ain't got no rights. Unions are supposed to help, but they're just another bunch of guys lookin' to make a buck off the backs of the poor. You got folks workin' themselves to death, and nobody even cares. It's a real shame, a real travesty.

So, this book writer, Fitzgerald, he's got tricks up his sleeve to make you feel a certain way about stuff.  He's like a magician with words, ya know? Sometimes he'll pair words together that don't usually go together, just to give ya a vibe. Other times, he picks a thing, like a color, and makes it mean somethin' special, then he uses that special meanin' to make ya feel somethin' about somethin' else.

He does this a lot with colors in his book *The Great Gatsby*. He's got these colors, like gold, green, white, gray, and red, and he gives 'em all these deep meanings. Then he uses 'em to make ya remember how somethin' makes ya feel.

Take white and gray, for example. He makes 'em mean somethin' like sameness, like everything's the same. White's a bit nicer, fancier, while gray's more old and faded, ya know?

He shows ya this right from the start, with everyone wearin' white. Daisy and Jordan, they're always in white. Heck, even Nick's wearin' white to Gatsby's party! And Tom's got on a white shirt when he meets Myrtle.  The only time folks ain't wearin' white is when Nick's at Gatsby's party, and then it's all these loud, bright colors.

Fitzgerald uses these colors everywhere, like when Nick goes to work, he goes down these "white chasms" in New York.  And the names at Gatsby's party? They're all just "gray names."  Even Catherine's apartment building looks like a big white cake, all the same.

He even uses white and gray for regular folks and places. Jordan and Daisy had a "white girlhood." There are "gray cars" and "gray land" in that depressing valley of ashes.  

Fitzgerald keeps us thinkin' about these colors, buildin' up this whole feelin' for 'em. Then, when he wants ya to think somethin' ain't important, or it's just part of the crowd, he uses white or gray.

Take Daisy, for example. After he's been using these colors everywhere, he describes Daisy all in white, in her white car. Suddenly, she doesn't seem so special anymore, just like somethin' Gatsby wants, somethin' uniform, like a pretty package. 

He does this with Daisy a few more times, makin' her seem more like a pretty picture than a real person. She's got a "gray haze" around her neck, and she's wearin' white again before that big showdown with Tom and Gatsby.

Well, let me tell ya, San Diego's a pretty darn good place to grow stuff. That sunshine and mild weather? Makes for some mighty fine tomatoes, citrus, and all sorts of veggies. You got your squash, your broccoli, herbs galore, even peaches and lemons. And don't forget the berries and peppers!

Seems like folks around here are real keen on their organic eats too. There's a whole heap of folks signed up for community-supported agriculture, waiting for their share of that fresh-picked goodness. And eggs and milk? Organic all the way, folks!

A lot of these farms, they ain't just about the crops. They let you take a gander at how they do things, even go for a hike or watch the birds. Seems like a good way to make a livin' while helpin' out the environment, ya know?

Now, organic farming ain't always easy. It takes a lot more elbow grease to keep those pests and weeds at bay without all the fancy chemicals. Plus, crops sometimes don't do as well as with the regular stuff. But, it sure does do wonders for the critters and plants around here. More biodiversity, that's what they call it.

But hold on, there's more to it!  These folks makin' a go of it with wildlife in mind, they gotta do all sorts of extra work. Plantin' special cover crops, makin' sure the animals have a good place to graze, even gettin' rid of those pesky invasives.  

So, this landowner I was talkin' about, he's got a real pickle on his hands. He wants to make a decent livin' and help the critters out too. That takes some know-how and a little help, ya see.

This land he's lookin' at, it's out near Potrero, a real beautiful spot.  It's got chaparral, grassland, and oak trees, all right next to that Cleveland National Forest.  They're sayin' there's all sorts of critters livin' there, some endangered, some just hangin' on.

Been sayin' this land's been around for ages, first the Native Americans, then some ranchers and folks sellin' firewood. Back in the day, this was a homestead, so it was probably used for grazin' or choppin' wood.

Now, I found this piece of property online and figured out what kind of help this farmer might be able to get. I even found a real organic farm nearby, doin' pretty much what I'm talkin' about.

Listen, everybody knows culture matters when you're tryin' to get somethin' done.  It ain't just about what a culture is, but what it ain't, you know?  It's not like everyone in a place is the same, like sayin' all Rednecks are stubborn or all them fancy Japanese are always playin' it nice.  That's just plain dumb talk.  

What you gotta do is figure out how that culture's gonna play out in the deal you're makin'.  You see the world through your own eyes, and it's natural to compare, but you gotta go deeper than that.

Think about it like this:  when you're dealin' with folks from a different place, you gotta learn their history, their hang-ups, the things they think are important.  Don't go tryin' to change 'em, just gotta respect it.  It's like when you're on someone else's turf - you gotta play by their rules, especially if you're the one with less to offer.  Treat 'em right, show 'em respect for their ways, and you'll get further.

And it ain't just countries, you know.  Inside any big company, there's a whole culture goin' on.  Some places are all about workin' 'til you drop, others are laid back.  How they dress, how they talk, who they hire - it all tells ya somethin' about their culture.  Some companies encourage helpin' others, others are all about makin' money.  Just look around you - there's all kinds of different ways to do business.

Values are the real key though.  They're the heart of a culture, the reason everything else is the way it is.  If a culture cares about lookin' good or gettin' along, they ain't gonna embarrass their boss to win a deal.  If they're all about makin' a tough bargain, they ain't gonna cave easy.  

So, before you walk into any kinda negotiation, do your homework.  Figure out the culture, what they stand for, what makes 'em tick.  And don't forget, get to know the folks you're dealin' with on a personal level too.  That's how you really make a deal.

Dang ol' psalm talkin' about how folks say there ain't no God, right?  Well, that's what Anselm and Aquinas are tryin' to prove wrong.  They both believe in the same God, the one from the Bible.  Now, we gotta figure out whose argument makes more sense, so we're gonna pretend they're both right about God existin'. 

Anselm, he thinks we gotta look inside ourselves to find God.  He says since we can think about God, He must be real.  Kinda like, if you can picture a dang ol' redneck in a pickup truck, that means there's gotta be rednecks in pickup trucks out there, right?  Anselm's sayin' that God's gotta be real 'cause we can think about Him.  He calls it faith, I reckon.

Aquinas, he's a different kinda fella.  He thinks we can prove God exists with logic and stuff, like lookin' at the world and sayin', "Hey, this ain't just happenin' by itself, there's gotta be a reason!"  He's got five different reasons, but they all boil down to sayin' that God makes sense, ya know?

Both of 'em got some good points, but neither one of 'em really convinces me that God's gotta be real.

Alright, so there was this dude, right? Way back in the day, like 5 or 600 BC, he was born a prince. But this dude, the one they'd later call Buddha, he decided to ditch the fancy life and go all spiritual. He figured out some stuff about how the world works, and his ideas started this whole religion called Buddhism. Now, the most straight-up kind of Buddhism is called Theravada, and it's been around for about 2,500 years. Things have changed a bit since Buddha was around, you know?

Like, in Sri Lanka, these guys still do this big water-cutting ceremony every year. Monks and regular folks, they all join in, and it's kinda important to them, even though Buddha never mentioned anything about it. It's like that with a lot of stuff in Theravada Buddhism—some stuff's changed from the old days, both the little stuff and the big stuff.  The monks and the regular folks who follow Buddhism, they've had to tweak their ideas a bit over time. It's like, life changes things, ya know?

We gotta talk about some words a lot in this here story. We're gonna say things like "internal" and "external," and "hostile" and "benign." Think of it this way: "internal" means something coming from inside the Buddhist group, whether you're a monk or not. "External" means something coming from folks outside of Buddhism. "Hostile" means something bad for Buddhism, like someone trying to mess it up. "Benign" means something that's not trying to help or hurt Buddhism, but might end up doing one or the other by accident.

First things first, let's get the basics of Theravada Buddhism down. Buddhists put their faith in the "Triple Gem"—the Buddha, his teachings (the Dhamma), and the community of Buddhists (the Sangha). The Dhamma is like a big library of Buddhist writings called the "Tripitaka."  There's the Sutta Pitaka with all the Buddha's teachings, the Vinaya Pitaka with the rules for monks, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka with the deep, philosophical stuff about Buddhism.

They talk about things like Anatta (no soul), Dukkha (suffering), and Anicca (everything changes).  They think that by understanding these things, you can escape Sansara, which is like a big wheel of life, death, and being reborn over and over.  And when you get out of that wheel, you get rid of Lobha (desire), Dosa (hatred), and Moha (delusion). That's when you become enlightened.

Listen, you ever hear about how the US and Mexico used to be like cat and dog, fightin' over everything?  They were at odds for like 57 years straight!  Back in the 1840s, we even went to war with 'em over Texas and parts of the Southwest.  It was a real mess, folks.  They call it the Mexican-American War, and we kicked their butts good.  But it weren't just that one fight, see?  They kept buttin' heads over things like religion, their way of life, and all sorts of stuff.  Kinda like how neighbors might argue over a fence or somethin'. 

This ain't nothin' new, though.  Countries that live next to each other, they tend to get into it sometimes.  Look at us and Cuba, or even with Canada sometimes.  It's just how things go.  You got some folks sayin' that we've had more trouble with Mexico and Cuba than any other country.  Maybe they got a point.

Now, religion played a big part in all this.  Back then, Americans didn't like Catholics much, and Mexicans, well, they were Catholic as can be.  Just like the Cold War, where we were against Russia 'cause of their communism, it was kinda like that, but with religion instead.  It ain't easy when you got different beliefs, you know?

These two countries, they had a lot of spats back then.  Mostly about land, and bandits crossin' the border and causin' trouble.  It took both sides sendin' in the troops to finally put a stop to it.  Eventually, though, things cooled down.  Mexico started dependin' on us more and more, and we weren't so interested in takin' their land anymore.

Fifteen years ago, bam! I got hit with this sickness, outta nowhere.  Didn't even know it existed!  I was a nurse back then, ya know, figured I'd always have a job, 'cause people always get sick.  That's what everyone kept sayin' growing up.  Truth is, I always wanted to be a scientist or a writer, maybe both, but  nursing seemed like the safe bet.  Well, here I am, 46, single, broke as a joke, and can't work.  Still can't, after 15 years on disability.  Got nothin' left,  barely gettin' by.  Every day is a fight,  feelin' like I'm losin' everything I got.  Nothing's certain anymore, except I couldn't have made it this long without my family and a few good friends.  'Cause when life throws you a real curveball,  strong don't mean a darn thing.

My point is,  life throws ya curveballs, big and small.  No use tryin' to predict 'em,  and sometimes,  no matter how prepared you are,  you just need a hand.  

Now, I get it, we gotta stop relyin' so much on the government.  It's a mess, that much is clear. But wouldn't it be better if folks started lookin' out for each other again?  Help when they can, ask for help when they need it.  Rather than everyone buildin' their own little bunkers.

Those folks talkin' 'bout rugged individualism,  they forget what really built this country.  It wasn't just grit, it was folks lookin' out for each other, sharin' what they had.  Those pioneers crossing the Rockies,  they didn't make it alone.

So yeah, be prepared!  I am.  Got my disaster kit, first aid, water filters,  even plastic sheeting for the windows,  just in case. Flashlights, batteries, candles, the whole shebang.  If you can grow your own food,  can it,  do it.  Wood stove,  if you got the space.  But while you're at it,  get to know your neighbors.

Alright, so you wanna know how critters change over time, right? Like, why they get all different lookin'?  Well, it ain't simple, ya know?  It's kinda like tryin' to figure out how to build a house just by lookin' at a picture of it. We've got some smart folks tryin' to figure this out with math, like tryin' to write down the rules of how a shell grows up, ya know? They're lookin' at these ancient seashells called Prunum and tryin' to see how they changed over time.

They're usin' fancy pictures and computer programs to make models of these shells, kinda like buildin' a 3D puzzle. They wanna see what shapes are possible, like what kinda twists and turns a shell can take. Then they're gonna compare that to real shells and see how close they get.

Think of a shell like a spiral staircase windin' around. Each step is a whorl, and the center pole is the columella. Some shells get bigger faster than others, and the line between each whorl is called a suture. The biggest whorl is the one at the bottom, and all the rest are called the spire.  

Anyways, they're tryin' to figure out the rules of the game, how these shells change shape over time.  It's like tryin' to figure out how a plant grows, but with shells!

Listen, here's the deal with Indonesia.  They're doin' alright, y'know, gettin' their water and sanitation squared away like they promised.  But when it comes to takin' care of moms and babies, they're fallin' behind.  Like, really fallin' behind.

Now, they're braggin' about makin' sure more babies are born with a doctor or somethin' around,  but let me tell ya, sometimes those "doctors" are just old ladies who don't know nothin' 'bout real medicine.  And that's why so many moms end up dyin' from bleedin' out after childbirth.  It's a mess, plain and simple.

On top of that, fewer kids are gettin' help for their belly aches, and nobody seems to be lookin' after 'em after they're born.  It's like they're just lettin' these kids fend for themselves.

And don't even get me started on the C-sections.  They're doin' them way too little, especially out in the sticks.  It's like the rich folks get all the good healthcare, while everyone else is stuck with whatever they can scrounge up.

So what's the answer?  Should they just keep throwin' money at this problem with a bunch of different programs, or should they fix the whole darn healthcare system?  It's a tough call.  Programmatic approaches are easier to manage, but they can suck up all the resources and leave other parts of the system starved.  Plus,  you end up with a bunch of different groups doin' the same thing, but not talkin' to each other.  It's a recipe for disaster.

Victorian novels are known for their super detailed descriptions and their focus on the rich and fancy folks back then. But there are a couple of books from that time, Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights, that don't quite fit that mold. They're kinda spooky and a little weird, which is different from most novels from that era. This weirdness actually makes the characters more interesting, giving us a better understanding of what makes them tick.

Take this passage from Oliver Twist:

“And now, hosts of bewildering and confusing ideas came crowding on his mind. He seemed to be still walking between Sikes and Crackit, who were angrily disputing: for the very words they said, sounded in his ears; and when he caught his own attention, … he found that he was talking to them…. Suddenly he started back at the report of fire arms; and there rose into the air loud cries and shouts; lights gleamed before his eyes, and all was noise and tumult, as some unseen hand bore him hurriedly away. Through all these rapid visions, there ran an undefined, uneasy consciousness of pain, which weared and tormented him incessantly.” 
(Dickens, 220)


These books often use mystery and dream-like scenes to do this, but they do it in different ways. In Oliver Twist, these strange happenings show us what's going on inside Oliver's head, his pain, and how he sees the world around him. When Oliver gets shot, he relives it all over again in a dream-like state as he tries to find help. 

This passage shows how out of control Oliver feels.  He's overwhelmed, and his pain is constant and linked with fear, not just shock.  It makes you wonder who's really in charge of his fate, because it's definitely not him.  He doesn't even try to fight back, even when his life is on the line.  This makes you think that maybe he's starting to give up hope, like Fagin has broken him and made him accept this miserable fate.


“The day passed off – day! There was no day; it was gone as soon as come – and night came on again; night so long, and yet so short; long in it’s dreadful silence and short in it’s fleeting ours."

A couple years back, I was workin' in this after-school program, helpin' out little kids with their schoolwork. I was pretty good at English and readin', so I'd help out with whatever those kids were strugglin' with. One time, they asked me to help this little fella named Adrian, maybe in third or fourth grade. He was havin' a real tough time readin'. I mean, it was just plain weird. Some letters he'd get right, but others, he'd butcher 'em somethin' fierce.

You see, Adrian was Latino, spoke perfect English, but his readin' was all messed up. We were hittin' a wall, I mean, I didn't know what to do! Then one day, Adrian's momma came to pick him up. Now, she didn't speak a lick of English. Just Spanish. I could barely spit out a few words myself, but we managed to get by. And that's when it hit me like a ton of bricks: Adrian could read just fine, he just didn't know the English alphabet that well.
